{"title_page": "Agneepath (1990 film)", "text_new": "{{About||the remake|Agneepath (2012 film)|the TV series|Agneepath (TV series)}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Agneepath\n| image          = Agneepath.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Mukul S. Anand]]\n| producer       = [[Yash Johar]]\n| screenplay     = [[Santosh Saroj]]<br>[[Kader Khan]]\n| story          = [[Santosh Saroj]]\n| starring       =[[Amitabh Bachchan]]<br>[[Mithun Chakraborty]]<br>[[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]]<br>[[Neelam Kothari]]<br>[[Danny Denzongpa]]<br>[[Rohini Hattangadi]]<br>[[Alok Nath]]\n| music          = {{unbulleted list|[[Laxmikant Pyarelal]]|[[Jean Michel Jarre]]|Anand Bakshi (lyrics)}}\n| cinematography = [[Pravin Bhatt]]\n| editing        = Waman Bhonsle\n| distributor    = [[Dharma Productions]] (India)<br>[[Warner Bros.]] (US VHS only)<br>[[TriStar Pictures]] (US DVD and Blu-ray)\n| released       = {{film date|df=y|1990|02|16}}\n| runtime        = 174 minutes\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| gross          ={{INRConvert|102.5|m}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=196&catName=MTk5MA== |title=Box office 1990 |work=Box office india |access-date=2 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017072637/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=196&catName=MTk5MA== |archive-date=17 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Agneepath''''' (English: ''The Path of Fire'') is a [[Bollywood films of 1990|1990]] Indian [[action film|action]]-[[drama film]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.livemint.com/Consumer/GXCD8vywatfXqFjObF5X8K/Ten-revenge-dramas-from-Bollywood.html |title=Ten revenge dramas from Bollywood |access-date=11 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214070858/https://www.livemint.com/Consumer/GXCD8vywatfXqFjObF5X8K/Ten-revenge-dramas-from-Bollywood.html |archive-date=14 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/no-one-can-dare-emulate-amitabh-bachchan-karan-johar/891910/ No one can dare emulate Amitabh Bachchan: Karan Johar]</ref> directed by [[Mukul Anand]]. It stars [[Amitabh Bachchan]] as the protagonist Vijay Deenanath Chauhan along with [[Mithun Chakraborty]], [[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]], [[Neelam Kothari]], [[Rohini Hattangadi]] and [[Danny Denzongpa]] as the antagonist [[Kancha Cheena]]. The film was produced by [[Yash Johar]].\n\nThe title was taken from a poem of the same name called 'Agneepath'<ref>{{cite web |last=Sayuj |first=Riku |url=http://wanderingmirages.wordpress.com/2012/02/01/agneepath-an-english-translation/ |title=Agneepath (\u0905\u0917\u094d\u0928\u093f\u092a\u0925) \u2013 A poem by Harivansh Rai Bachchan |publisher=Wandering Mirages |date=1 February 2012 |accessdate=1 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210034353/http://wanderingmirages.wordpress.com/2012/02/01/agneepath-an-english-translation/ |archive-date=10 February 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> which was penned by [[Harivansh Rai Bachchan]], [[Amitabh Bachchan|Amitabh's]] father, and which is recited at the beginning of the movie and creates a thematic link that continues through the movie, particularly in the climax, both literally and metaphorically.\n\nAgneepath has grown into a strong [[cult film]] over the years. It is considered a milestone in Bachchan's career, and in the league of his all-time great movies. [[Amitabh Bachchan]] received his first [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] at the [[38th National Film Awards]] for his performance. [[Mithun Chakraborty]] received the [[Filmfare Best Supporting Actor Award]]. The film, despite being the tenth highest-grosser of 1990, had collections way below its high budget, and thus, the film recorded as ''flop'' at the box-office. The film was remade in 2012 [[Agneepath (2012 film)|with the same title]], by Johar's son [[Karan Johar]], as a tribute to his father. This movie seems to have some inspiration from 1983 [[Al Pacino]] hit movie [[Scarface (1983 film)|''Scarface'']] {{Citation Needed|date=April 2020|reason=Please provide verified articles to justify the claim}}.\n\n==Plot==\nMuch-loved village schoolmaster Deenanath Chauhan ([[Alok Nath]]) strongly opposes the plans of [[Kancha Cheena]], an underworld don ([[Danny Dengzongpa]]) and his band of gangsters to set up a base for heroin smuggling. After being discredited in a set-up scandal and lynched by the manipulated villagers, his family is evicted and made destitute much to Cheena's advantage. Swearing revenge after his father's murder and the attempted rape of his mother Suhasini Chauhan ([[Rohini Hattangadi]]) go unpunished, and with a burning desire to clear his father's name, his son Vijay ([[Amitabh Bachchan]]) takes on the responsibilities of caring for his mother and sister Siksha ([[Neelam Kothari|Neelam]]) that, by a strange twist of fate, cause him to become a gangster in his own right. Working his way up the ladder and attaining notoriety as an underworld kingpin, Vijay suffers an assassination attempt by fellow gangsters after he refuses to co-operate with their drug-smuggling operations. Left to die, he is discovered by Krishnan Iyer M.A. ([[Mithun Chakraborty]]) who transports him to hospital and saves his life, and who eventually finds employment as Siksha's bodyguard. During his time in hospital, Vijay is cared for by Nurse Mary Matthew ([[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]]).\n\nVijay avenges his assassination attempt by killing his killers one by one, but his mother strongly disapproves of his murderous and gangster tendencies and drives him away from home after chastising him for dirtying the good name of his father. Vijay, hurt and upset, seeks solace in Mary's arms and begins a relationship with her. Siksha is then kidnapped and held in a slum by a gangster who wants to avenge the death of his associates killed by Vijay, and an unsuccessful rescue attempt by Krishnan ends up with the two of them brawling. Vijay hears of this and arrives to kill the gangster in a fit of rage. But this close encounter between Krishnan and Siksha causes a growing intimacy between the two of them and they fall in love with each other. Vijay is outraged and strongly protests against the relationship to his mother, but is rebuffed again when his mother disowns him a second time and considers Krishnan her \"good son\". Stung and deeply hurt by this slight, he again seeks solace in Mary and later marries her and resolves to do things \"in the right way\" to gain his mother's favour.\n\nAfter cutting a deal with Kancha Cheena to allow him access into his old village, Vijay sets in motion a number of strategies that undercut Cheena's criminal operations and gain him the legal ownership of the village. Revenge is a dish best served cold as Vijay informs Cheena of his identity as the son of Deenanath Chauhan, lands Cheena in jail and arranges for Cheena's associates to testify against him in court. Vijay returns the village to his mother and finds himself back in her favour, but Cheena ensures his release by arranging for the witnesses to be gunned down and Vijay's family to be kidnapped and held hostage. This is the last straw for Vijay who is forced to return to his criminal ways and to walk the \"Path of Fire\" in order to rescue them. An almighty struggle takes place as Cheena bombs every building and demolishes the whole village before he is killed by Vijay's bare hands. But Vijay does not survive; he dies of a bullet wound in the lap of his mother at the site of his old house. His mother realises that everything Vijay had done until then had been for the ultimate purpose of restoring the good name of Deenanath Chauhan, and she weeps over his body piteously along with Krishnan, Siksha and Mary.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Amitabh Bachchan]] as Vijay Deenanath Chauhan\n*[[Mithun Chakraborty]] as Krishnan Iyer M.A.\n*[[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]] as Mary Mathew\n*[[Danny Denzongpa]] as Kancha Cheena (Underworld Kingpin)\n*[[Neelam Kothari]] as Siksha Chauhan\n*[[Goga Kapoor]] as Dinkar Rao\n*[[Alok Nath]] as Master Deenanath Chauhan\n*[[Rohini Hattangadi]] as Suhasini Chauhan\n*[[Sharat Saxena]] as Terralin (Rival Gang leader)\n*[[Tinnu Anand]] as Nathu\n*[[Vikram Gokhale]] as Commissioner M. S. Gaitonde\n*[[Archana Puran Singh]] as Shanti aka Laila\n*[[Avtar Gill]] as Usman Bhai (Rival Gang leader)\n*[[Shammi (actress)|Shammi]] as Tara Bai\n*[[Bob Christo]] as Gora\n*[[Shakti Kapoor]] as Himself in the song ''[[Ali Baba]]''\n*[[Asha Sachdev]] as Chanda Bai\n*[[Deepak Shirke]] as Anna Shetty (Rival Gang leader)\n*[[Pradeep Rawat (actor)|Pradeep Rawat]] as Vijay's Henchman\n*[[Master Manjunath]] as Young Vijay Chauhan\n*[[Anjan Srivastav]] as Police Constable\n*[[Tabassum]]\n*[[Monty Sharma]]\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Amitabhbachchan28529.jpg|right|thumb|225px|Amitabh Bachchan during the shoot of ''Agneepath''.]]\nA characteristic feature of the movie was the dark undertones and the grim atmosphere of the film, which was unusual for any of Amitabh Bachchan's films. It was noted that the film was \"grim\" due to the protagonist, Vijay Chauhan bloodlust and ferocity.<ref name=\"agneepath2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moviediva.com/MD_root/reviewpages/MDHindiBlurbsOld.htm|title=Moviediva: Hindi Movie Reviews; Agneepath(1990)|work=Moviediva|access-date=7 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205194019/http://www.moviediva.com/MD_root/reviewpages/MDHindiBlurbsOld.htm|archive-date=5 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The film utilised a lot of dark distortions in the imagery, which were a common theme in some Gangster Films.<ref name=\"agneepath3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/trivia|title=IMDB-Agneepath: Trivia|work=IMDB|access-date=28 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408143436/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/trivia|archive-date=8 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Mithun Chakraborty's unique role of Krishnan Iyer was inspired by one of his roommates of his struggling days, before he became a popular film star. In his struggling days Chakraborty used to be room sharing with Devio who used to pay 150 Rupees while Chakraborty Used to pay 75 Rupees. Devio had the a bed while Chakraborty used to sleep on the floor, one specific time Chakraborty used his bed whilst he was at work and when Devio came back he scolded Chakraborty. This incident remained with Chakraborty and he put Devio's character on screen. Tinnu Anand, who played the role of the Village Drunkard, shaved his head to obtain the age difference between him and Amitabh Bachchan.<ref name=\"agneepath3\" /> The film was shot extensively in Bombay in several locations such as Andheri, Goregaon, and Colaba.<ref name=\"agneepath4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/locations|title=Agneepath (1990) - filming locations|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419020749/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/locations |date=19 April 2015|archive-date=19 April 2015}}</ref> The locations and the photography drew positive feedback from critics.<ref name=\"agneepath6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/blast-from-the-past-agneepath-1990-review/|title=Blast from the Past: A review of the 1990 Mukul Anand's Agneepath, by Komal Nahta|work=Koimoi|access-date=7 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131153553/http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/blast-from-the-past-agneepath-1990-review/|archive-date=31 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nWhen released, Agneepath was a failure, both at the box office as well as among the critics. However, [[Karan Johar]] recounts in an interview how younger city based audiences thought it was a cool film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johan|first1=Karan|title=Interview with Karan Johan : Indu Mirani|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tBTUJQdXFkw|website=You Tube|publisher=The Boss Dialogues|accessdate=18 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105225440/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tBTUJQdXFkw|archive-date=5 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Over the top, inane songs\", dialogues \"veering towards melodrama\" and, more importantly, Amitabh Bachchan's experimentation with his voice did not go well with the masses and the critics alike. Film Trade Analyst Komal Nahta wrote thus about Bachchan's voice, : \"But the biggest undoing of the film is Amitabh Bachchan\u2019s voice. He has spoken the dialogue in a different voice (inspired by [[Marlon Brando]] in [[The Godfather]]) which will not be accepted by the audience. Further the mixing not being clear, his dialogues are incomprehensible at places.\" He further wrote that the film lacked a gripping drama, well-set script, and that even the murder scenes lacked excitement.<ref name=\"agneepath6\" /> Satish Naidu in his review noted that the narrative had a slow pace in the last hour. Another fact that worked against the advantage of the film was its weak story. Rediff's review of Agneepath suggested that perhaps, the grim, violent, aggressive and dark portrayal of the underbelly of Bombay's underworld had worked against the film.<ref name=\"agneepathredifffours\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-revisiting-amitabh-bachchan-s-agneepath/20120124.htm|title=Revisiting Amitabh Bachchan's Agneepath (Slide 1)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210000326/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-revisiting-amitabh-bachchan-s-agneepath/20120124.htm |date=10 February 2012|archive-date=10 February 2012|work=Rediff Movies}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the National Award for the best actor being bestowed on Amitabh Bachchan changed the perspective in which the film was appreciated. Over the years, favourable reviews trickling in made Agneepath a cult classic. Currently, Agneepath has been rated 7.7 on a scale of 10 in the [[Internet Movie Database]] by 7,555 users.<ref name=\"IMDbrating\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/|title=IMDb: Agneepath(1990)|work=IMDB|access-date=28 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330192604/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/|archive-date=30 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], 93% of 715 user ratings favour the movie.<ref name=\"rottentomatorating\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/agneepath/|title=Rotten Tomatoes: Agneepath(1990)-Amitabh Bachchan|work=Rotten Tomatoes|access-date=7 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131185851/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/agneepath/|archive-date=31 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sanjay Dutt]], the actor who plays Kancha Cheena's role in the [[Agneepath(2012 film)|remake]] praised the film saying that it was well ahead of its time when asked about the original film- : \"I loved the original film and if I was the whole of audience, I would have made it a big hit. I think may be the film was too ahead of times. Mukul is a brilliant director and his vision was so much ahead of his time.\"<ref name=\"agneepathsanjayopinion\">{{cite web|url=http://bollywooders.com/bollywood-news/sanjay-dutt-praises-amitabh-bachchans-agneepath/ |accessdate=8 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203175909/http://bollywooders.com/bollywood-news/sanjay-dutt-praises-amitabh-bachchans-agneepath/ |archivedate=3 February 2012 |title=Sanjay Dutt praises Amitabh's Agneepath: Bollywooders|work=Bollywooders}}</ref>\nSatish Naidu commented in his blog that Agneepath's direction, camera work and cinematography \"had some serious physicality going for the film[there]\". He further drove home his opinion, describing the betrayal of a certain \"undeveloped terrain below\" by the jagged, staccato-like movements of the camera work. Further, Mr.Naidu praised the way in which Mukul Anand portrayed Amitabh Bachchan in the film. An interesting aspect of the film was its cinematography, handled by [[Pravin Bhatt]], which has been described as \"marvelous\" due to the \"beautiful scenes shot in Mauritius. The ship bombing scene was executed well, and that the portrayal of the picturesque scenery of trees and fields in full bloom (in the songs, especially) met with rave reviews. Movie Reviewer Peter Nepstad in his blog, the \"Illuminated Lantern\" wrote that:\n:\"Agneepath is deliriously melodramatic. The first thirty minutes, the prologue of the film if you will, in the village of his youth, ranks among the best openings of any Bollywood film I've ever seen. Afterwards, when most Bollywood films crank it down for some syrupy romance or goofy comedy, Agneepath plops its adult protagonist right in the middle of a gang fight. Often a film has a great set piece at the beginning, then deflates by the end, but Agneepath continues amping up the conflict from beginning to end, from riots in a village to riots in a city to mudfights in the slums to swordfights in the middle of a festival.\"<ref name=\"agneepathilluminelantern\">{{cite web|url=http://www.illuminatedlantern.com/cinema/review/archives/agneepath.php|title=Illuminated Lantern: A blog describing the heart of South Asian Cinema-Agneepath(1990) directed by Mukul.S.Anand|work=Illuminated Lantern|access-date=21 February 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223235509/http://www.illuminatedlantern.com/cinema/review/archives/agneepath.php|archive-date=23 February 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe movie's review in Rediff.com, mentioned that: \"Agneepath, despite its amplified sentimentality, strong language and violence works on account of this very dynamism. \"<ref name=\"agneepathrediff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-revisiting-amitabh-bachchan-s-agneepath/20120124.htm|title=Rediff.com-Movies-Reviews-Revisiting Amitabh Bachchan's Agneepath(Slide 3)|work=Rediff|access-date=8 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210000326/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-revisiting-amitabh-bachchan-s-agneepath/20120124.htm|archive-date=10 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Box office==\nAccording to trade website [[Box Office India]], the gross collection of the movie was Rs 10,25,00,000, way below the film's budget and so despite being among the top grossers of the year the film was a flop.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Tracklist\n| headline        = Songs\n| extra_column    = Playback\n| all_music       = [[Laxmikant Pyarelal]], [[Jean Michel Jarre]]\n\n| title1  = Kisko Tha Pata\n| extra1  = [[SP Balasubramanyam]], [[Alka Yagnik]]\n\n| title2  = I Am Krishnan Iyer M. A.\n| extra2  = [[SP Balasubramanyam]]\n\n| title3  = Ali Baba Mil Gaye Chalis Choron Se\n| extra3  = [[Runa Laila]], [[Aadesh]]\n\n| title4  = Ganpati Apne Gaon Chale\n| extra4  = [[Sudesh Bhosle]], [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]], [[Anupama Deshpande]]\n}}\n\nThe film featured great background music, but songs were rather not exciting{{POV statement|date=April 2020}}. Rather unusually, for a [[Bollywood]] film of the time, a West African track was used in the film. [[Guinean]] singer [[Mory Kant\u00e9's]] hit [[Y\u00e9 k\u00e9 y\u00e9 k\u00e9]] appears in the film, but is not on the soundtrack. The lyrics were penned by [[Anand Bakshi]].\n\n==Awards==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1990\n| [[Amitabh Bachchan]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Actor]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Mithun Chakraborty]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Rohini Hattangadi]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress]]\n| {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Remake==\n{{main|Agneepath (2012 film)}}\nIn an interview with The Times of India, [[Karan Johar]] explained that he had the intention of remaking the original Agneepath ever since the film released 22 years ago, because according to him, the failure of the film broke his father's heart.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-26/news-interviews/30663491_1_agneepath-karan-johar-kancha-cheena | work=The Times of India | title=Agneepath broke my father's heart: Karan Johar | date=26 January 2012 | access-date=14 April 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023164409/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-26/news-interviews/30663491_1_agneepath-karan-johar-kancha-cheena | archive-date=23 October 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> The idea of the remake materialised on the sets of Johar's film ''[[My Name Is Khan]]'' in which Karan Malhotra was an associate director. Johar told Malhotra his desire to remake the original film and asked him to revisit it again, to which he agreed immediately.\n\nHrithik Roshan played the lead role of Vijay Deenanath Chauhan and Sanjay Dutt plays the role of the antagonist Kancha Cheena.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2010/nov/281110-Agneepath-remake-Sanjay-Dutt-Karan-Johar.htm |title=Sanjay Dutt is the bad man now |work=MidDay |access-date=15 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617084139/http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2010/nov/281110-Agneepath-remake-Sanjay-Dutt-Karan-Johar.htm |archive-date=17 June 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Priyanka Chopra was the female lead. The character of Krishnan Iyer played by Mithun Chakraborty in the original was removed and Rishi Kapoor played a newly introduced negative character, Rauf Lala.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/article/30/2011010620110106022045461abd4a9fe/Rishi-to-do-a-%E2%80%98looks-test%E2%80%99-for-Agneepath.html |title=Rishi to do a 'looks test' for Agneepath |work=Mumbai Mirror |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110109013448/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/article/30/2011010620110106022045461abd4a9fe/Rishi-to-do-a-%E2%80%98looks-test%E2%80%99-for-Agneepath.html |archivedate=9 January 2011 }}</ref> Other members of the cast include Om Puri and Zarina Wahab<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianage.com/bollywood/zarina-star-agneepath-remake-782 |title=Zarina to star in Agneepath remake |work=Asianage |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113035328/http://www.asianage.com/bollywood/zarina-star-agneepath-remake-782 |archivedate=13 January 2011 }}</ref> among others.\n\nShooting of the film mostly took place in Diu and Mumbai's film city. Originally slated for release on 20 January, ''Agneepath'' was postponed by a week to 26 January 2012. Unlike the original, the remake opened to positive responses from critics and the audience. ''[[Agneepath (2012 film)|Agneepath]]'' collected Rs 217.5&nbsp;million (US$4.34 million) on the opening day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3968&nCat= |title=Box Office 2012|work=Box Office India |access-date=14 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419165202/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3968&nCat= |archive-date=19 April 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to review aggregator Review Gang, professional critics have given the film a rating of 6.5 stars out of 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewgang.com/movies/208-Agneepath-Review |title=Agneepath review |work=Reviewgang |accessdate=14 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413140643/http://www.reviewgang.com/movies/208-Agneepath-Review |archivedate=13 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> The film did fantastic business at the box office and entered the 100 crore club.\n\nThe film was also modified and remade in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as [[Sivasakthi]], starring [[Sathyaraj]] and [[Prabhu Ganesan]] directed by [[Suresh Krissna]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|URL=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219234905/http://www3.dharma-production.com:80/FMovie/FMovieDetails.aspx?movieid=8bc11b19-2a31-4b2d-b1b3-0428da32d2e8|Agneepath (Path of Fire)}}\n* {{IMDb title|0098999|Agneepath}}\n\n{{Dharma Productions}}\n\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about organised crime in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actor National Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mukul S. Anand]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Maharashtra Police]]\n[[Category:Hindi films remade in other languages]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the remake|Agneepath (2012 film)|the TV series|Agneepath (TV series)}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Agneepath\n| image          = Agneepath.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Mukul S. Anand]]\n| producer       = [[Yash Johar]]\n| screenplay     = [[Santosh Saroj]]<br>[[Kader Khan]]\n| story          = [[Santosh Saroj]]\n| starring       =[[Amitabh Bachchan]]<br>[[Mithun Chakraborty]]<br>[[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]]<br>[[Neelam Kothari]]<br>[[Danny Denzongpa]]<br>[[Rohini Hattangadi]]<br>[[Alok Nath]]\n| music          = {{unbulleted list|[[Laxmikant Pyarelal]]|[[Jean Michel Jarre]]|Anand Bakshi (lyrics)}}\n| cinematography = [[Pravin Bhatt]]\n| editing        = Waman Bhonsle\n| distributor    = [[Dharma Productions]] (India)<br>[[Warner Bros.]] (US VHS only)<br>[[TriStar Pictures]] (US DVD and Blu-ray)\n| released       = {{film date|df=y|1990|02|16}}\n| runtime        = 174 minutes\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| gross          ={{INRConvert|102.5|m}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=196&catName=MTk5MA== |title=Box office 1990 |work=Box office india |access-date=2 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017072637/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=196&catName=MTk5MA== |archive-date=17 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Agneepath''''' (English: ''The Path of Fire'') is a [[Bollywood films of 1990|1990]] Indian [[action film|action]]-[[drama film]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.livemint.com/Consumer/GXCD8vywatfXqFjObF5X8K/Ten-revenge-dramas-from-Bollywood.html |title=Ten revenge dramas from Bollywood |access-date=11 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214070858/https://www.livemint.com/Consumer/GXCD8vywatfXqFjObF5X8K/Ten-revenge-dramas-from-Bollywood.html |archive-date=14 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/no-one-can-dare-emulate-amitabh-bachchan-karan-johar/891910/ No one can dare emulate Amitabh Bachchan: Karan Johar]</ref> directed by [[Mukul Anand]]. It stars [[Amitabh Bachchan]] as the protagonist Vijay Deenanath Chauhan along with [[Mithun Chakraborty]], [[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]], [[Neelam Kothari]], [[Rohini Hattangadi]] and [[Danny Denzongpa]] as the antagonist [[Kancha Cheena]]. The film was produced by [[Yash Johar]].\n\nThe title was taken from a poem of the same name called 'Agneepath'<ref>{{cite web |last=Sayuj |first=Riku |url=http://wanderingmirages.wordpress.com/2012/02/01/agneepath-an-english-translation/ |title=Agneepath (\u0905\u0917\u094d\u0928\u093f\u092a\u0925) \u2013 A poem by Harivansh Rai Bachchan |publisher=Wandering Mirages |date=1 February 2012 |accessdate=1 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210034353/http://wanderingmirages.wordpress.com/2012/02/01/agneepath-an-english-translation/ |archive-date=10 February 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> which was penned by [[Harivansh Rai Bachchan]], [[Amitabh Bachchan|Amitabh's]] father, and which is recited at the beginning of the movie and creates a thematic link that continues through the movie, particularly in the climax, both literally and metaphorically.\n\nAgneepath has grown into a strong [[cult film]] over the years. It is considered a milestone in Bachchan's career, and in the league of his all-time great movies. [[Amitabh Bachchan]] received his first [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] at the [[38th National Film Awards]] for his performance. [[Mithun Chakraborty]] received the [[Filmfare Best Supporting Actor Award]]. The film, despite being the tenth highest-grosser of 1990, had collections way below its high budget, and thus, the film recorded as ''flop'' at the box-office. The film was remade in 2012 [[Agneepath (2012 film)|with the same title]], by Johar's son [[Karan Johar]], as a tribute to his father. This movie seems to have some inspiration from 1983 [[Al Pacino]] hit movie [[Scarface (1983 film)|''Scarface'']] {{Citation Needed|date=April 2020|reason=Please provide verified articles to justify the claim}}.\n\n==Plot==\nMuch-loved village schoolmaster Deenanath Chauhan ([[Alok Nath]]) strongly opposes the plans of [[Kancha Cheena]], an underworld don ([[Danny Dengzongpa]]) and his band of gangsters to set up a base for heroin smuggling. After being discredited in a set-up scandal and lynched by the manipulated villagers, his family is evicted and made destitute much to Cheena's advantage. Swearing revenge after his father's murder and the attempted rape of his mother Suhasini Chauhan ([[Rohini Hattangadi]]) go unpunished, and with a burning desire to clear his father's name, his son Vijay ([[Amitabh Bachchan]]) takes on the responsibilities of caring for his mother and sister Siksha ([[Neelam Kothari|Neelam]]) that, by a strange twist of fate, cause him to become a gangster in his own right. Working his way up the ladder and attaining notoriety as an underworld kingpin, Vijay suffers an assassination attempt by fellow gangsters after he refuses to co-operate with their drug-smuggling operations. Left to die, he is discovered by Krishnan Iyer M.A. ([[Mithun Chakraborty]]) who transports him to hospital and saves his life, and who eventually finds employment as Siksha's bodyguard. During his time in hospital, Vijay is cared for by Nurse Mary Matthew ([[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]]).\n\nVijay avenges his assassination attempt by killing his killers one by one, but his mother strongly disapproves of his murderous and gangster tendencies and drives him away from home after chastising him for dirtying the good name of his father. Vijay, hurt and upset, seeks solace in Mary's arms and begins a relationship with her. Siksha is then kidnapped and held in a slum by a gangster who wants to avenge the death of his associates killed by Vijay, and an unsuccessful rescue attempt by Krishnan ends up with the two of them brawling. Vijay hears of this and arrives to kill the gangster in a fit of rage. But this close encounter between Krishnan and Siksha causes a growing intimacy between the two of them and they fall in love with each other. Vijay is outraged and strongly protests against the relationship to his mother, but is rebuffed again when his mother disowns him a second time and considers Krishnan her \"good son\". Stung and deeply hurt by this slight, he again seeks solace in Mary and later marries her and resolves to do things \"in the right way\" to gain his mother's favour.\n\nAfter cutting a deal with Kancha Cheena to allow him access into his old village, Vijay sets in motion a number of strategies that undercut Cheena's criminal operations and gain him the legal ownership of the village. Revenge is a dish best served cold as Vijay informs Cheena of his identity as the son of Deenanath Chauhan, lands Cheena in jail and arranges for Cheena's associates to testify against him in court. Vijay returns the village to his mother and finds himself back in her favour, but Cheena ensures his release by arranging for the witnesses to be gunned down and Vijay's family to be kidnapped and held hostage. This is the last straw for Vijay who is forced to return to his criminal ways and to walk the \"Path of Fire\" in order to rescue them. An almighty struggle takes place as Cheena bombs every building and demolishes the whole village before he is killed by Vijay's bare hands. But Vijay does not survive; he dies of a bullet wound in the lap of his mother at the site of his old house. His mother realises that everything Vijay had done until then had been for the ultimate purpose of restoring the good name of Deenanath Chauhan, and she weeps over his body piteously along with Krishnan, Siksha and Mary.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Amitabh Bachchan]] as Vijay Deenanath Chauhan\n*[[Mithun Chakraborty]] as Krishnan Iyer M.A.\n*[[Madhavi]] as Mary Mathew\n*[[Danny Denzongpa]] as Kancha Cheena (Underworld Kingpin)\n*[[Neelam Kothari]] as Siksha Chauhan\n*[[Goga Kapoor]] as Dinkar Rao\n*[[Alok Nath]] as Master Deenanath Chauhan\n*[[Rohini Hattangadi]] as Suhasini Chauhan\n*[[Sharat Saxena]] as Terralin (Rival Gang leader)\n*[[Tinnu Anand]] as Nathu\n*[[Vikram Gokhale]] as Commissioner M. S. Gaitonde\n*[[Archana Puran Singh]] as Shanti aka Laila\n*[[Avtar Gill]] as Usman Bhai (Rival Gang leader)\n*[[Shammi]] as Tara Bai\n*[[Bob Christo]] as Gora\n*[[Shakti Kapoor]] as Himself in the song ''[[Ali Baba]]''\n*[[Asha Sachdev]] as Chanda Bai\n*[[Deepak Shirke]] as Anna Shetty (Rival Gang leader)\n*[[Pradeep Rawat]] as Vijay's Henchman\n*[[Master Manjunath]] as Young Vijay Chauhan\n*[[Anjan Srivastav]] as Police Constable\n*[[Tabassum]]\n*[[Monty Sharma]]\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Amitabhbachchan28529.jpg|right|thumb|225px|Amitabh Bachchan during the shoot of ''Agneepath''.]]\nA characteristic feature of the movie was the dark undertones and the grim atmosphere of the film, which was unusual for any of Amitabh Bachchan's films. It was noted that the film was \"grim\" due to the protagonist, Vijay Chauhan bloodlust and ferocity.<ref name=\"agneepath2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moviediva.com/MD_root/reviewpages/MDHindiBlurbsOld.htm|title=Moviediva: Hindi Movie Reviews; Agneepath(1990)|work=Moviediva|access-date=7 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205194019/http://www.moviediva.com/MD_root/reviewpages/MDHindiBlurbsOld.htm|archive-date=5 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The film utilised a lot of dark distortions in the imagery, which were a common theme in some Gangster Films.<ref name=\"agneepath3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/trivia|title=IMDB-Agneepath: Trivia|work=IMDB|access-date=28 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408143436/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/trivia|archive-date=8 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Mithun Chakraborty's unique role of Krishnan Iyer was inspired by one of his roommates of his struggling days, before he became a popular film star. In his struggling days Chakraborty used to be room sharing with Devio who used to pay 150 Rupees while Chakraborty Used to pay 75 Rupees. Devio had the a bed while Chakraborty used to sleep on the floor, one specific time Chakraborty used his bed whilst he was at work and when Devio came back he scolded Chakraborty. This incident remained with Chakraborty and he put Devio's character on screen. Tinnu Anand, who played the role of the Village Drunkard, shaved his head to obtain the age difference between him and Amitabh Bachchan.<ref name=\"agneepath3\" /> The film was shot extensively in Bombay in several locations such as Andheri, Goregaon, and Colaba.<ref name=\"agneepath4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/locations|title=Agneepath (1990) - filming locations|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419020749/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/locations |date=19 April 2015|archive-date=19 April 2015}}</ref> The locations and the photography drew positive feedback from critics.<ref name=\"agneepath6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/blast-from-the-past-agneepath-1990-review/|title=Blast from the Past: A review of the 1990 Mukul Anand's Agneepath, by Komal Nahta|work=Koimoi|access-date=7 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131153553/http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/blast-from-the-past-agneepath-1990-review/|archive-date=31 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nWhen released, Agneepath was a failure, both at the box office as well as among the critics. However, [[Karan Johar]] recounts in an interview how younger city based audiences thought it was a cool film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johan|first1=Karan|title=Interview with Karan Johan : Indu Mirani|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tBTUJQdXFkw|website=You Tube|publisher=The Boss Dialogues|accessdate=18 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105225440/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tBTUJQdXFkw|archive-date=5 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Over the top, inane songs\", dialogues \"veering towards melodrama\" and, more importantly, Amitabh Bachchan's experimentation with his voice did not go well with the masses and the critics alike. Film Trade Analyst Komal Nahta wrote thus about Bachchan's voice, : \"But the biggest undoing of the film is Amitabh Bachchan\u2019s voice. He has spoken the dialogue in a different voice (inspired by [[Marlon Brando]] in [[The Godfather]]) which will not be accepted by the audience. Further the mixing not being clear, his dialogues are incomprehensible at places.\" He further wrote that the film lacked a gripping drama, well-set script, and that even the murder scenes lacked excitement.<ref name=\"agneepath6\" /> Satish Naidu in his review noted that the narrative had a slow pace in the last hour. Another fact that worked against the advantage of the film was its weak story. Rediff's review of Agneepath suggested that perhaps, the grim, violent, aggressive and dark portrayal of the underbelly of Bombay's underworld had worked against the film.<ref name=\"agneepathredifffours\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-revisiting-amitabh-bachchan-s-agneepath/20120124.htm|title=Revisiting Amitabh Bachchan's Agneepath (Slide 1)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210000326/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-revisiting-amitabh-bachchan-s-agneepath/20120124.htm |date=10 February 2012|archive-date=10 February 2012|work=Rediff Movies}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the National Award for the best actor being bestowed on Amitabh Bachchan changed the perspective in which the film was appreciated. Over the years, favourable reviews trickling in made Agneepath a cult classic. Currently, Agneepath has been rated 7.7 on a scale of 10 in the [[Internet Movie Database]] by 7,555 users.<ref name=\"IMDbrating\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/|title=IMDb: Agneepath(1990)|work=IMDB|access-date=28 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330192604/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098999/|archive-date=30 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], 93% of 715 user ratings favour the movie.<ref name=\"rottentomatorating\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/agneepath/|title=Rotten Tomatoes: Agneepath(1990)-Amitabh Bachchan|work=Rotten Tomatoes|access-date=7 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131185851/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/agneepath/|archive-date=31 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sanjay Dutt]], the actor who plays Kancha Cheena's role in the [[Agneepath(2012 film)|remake]] praised the film saying that it was well ahead of its time when asked about the original film- : \"I loved the original film and if I was the whole of audience, I would have made it a big hit. I think may be the film was too ahead of times. Mukul is a brilliant director and his vision was so much ahead of his time.\"<ref name=\"agneepathsanjayopinion\">{{cite web|url=http://bollywooders.com/bollywood-news/sanjay-dutt-praises-amitabh-bachchans-agneepath/ |accessdate=8 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203175909/http://bollywooders.com/bollywood-news/sanjay-dutt-praises-amitabh-bachchans-agneepath/ |archivedate=3 February 2012 |title=Sanjay Dutt praises Amitabh's Agneepath: Bollywooders|work=Bollywooders}}</ref>\nSatish Naidu commented in his blog that Agneepath's direction, camera work and cinematography \"had some serious physicality going for the film[there]\". He further drove home his opinion, describing the betrayal of a certain \"undeveloped terrain below\" by the jagged, staccato-like movements of the camera work. Further, Mr.Naidu praised the way in which Mukul Anand portrayed Amitabh Bachchan in the film. An interesting aspect of the film was its cinematography, handled by [[Pravin Bhatt]], which has been described as \"marvelous\" due to the \"beautiful scenes shot in Mauritius. The ship bombing scene was executed well, and that the portrayal of the picturesque scenery of trees and fields in full bloom (in the songs, especially) met with rave reviews. Movie Reviewer Peter Nepstad in his blog, the \"Illuminated Lantern\" wrote that:\n:\"Agneepath is deliriously melodramatic. The first thirty minutes, the prologue of the film if you will, in the village of his youth, ranks among the best openings of any Bollywood film I've ever seen. Afterwards, when most Bollywood films crank it down for some syrupy romance or goofy comedy, Agneepath plops its adult protagonist right in the middle of a gang fight. Often a film has a great set piece at the beginning, then deflates by the end, but Agneepath continues amping up the conflict from beginning to end, from riots in a village to riots in a city to mudfights in the slums to swordfights in the middle of a festival.\"<ref name=\"agneepathilluminelantern\">{{cite web|url=http://www.illuminatedlantern.com/cinema/review/archives/agneepath.php|title=Illuminated Lantern: A blog describing the heart of South Asian Cinema-Agneepath(1990) directed by Mukul.S.Anand|work=Illuminated Lantern|access-date=21 February 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223235509/http://www.illuminatedlantern.com/cinema/review/archives/agneepath.php|archive-date=23 February 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe movie's review in Rediff.com, mentioned that: \"Agneepath, despite its amplified sentimentality, strong language and violence works on account of this very dynamism. \"<ref name=\"agneepathrediff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-revisiting-amitabh-bachchan-s-agneepath/20120124.htm|title=Rediff.com-Movies-Reviews-Revisiting Amitabh Bachchan's Agneepath(Slide 3)|work=Rediff|access-date=8 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210000326/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-revisiting-amitabh-bachchan-s-agneepath/20120124.htm|archive-date=10 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Box office==\nAccording to trade website [[Box Office India]], the gross collection of the movie was Rs 10,25,00,000, way below the film's budget and so despite being among the top grossers of the year the film was a flop.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Tracklist\n| headline        = Songs\n| extra_column    = Playback\n| all_music       = [[Laxmikant Pyarelal]], [[Jean Michel Jarre]]\n\n| title1  = Kisko Tha Pata\n| extra1  = [[SP Balasubramanyam]], [[Alka Yagnik]]\n\n| title2  = I Am Krishnan Iyer M. A.\n| extra2  = [[SP Balasubramanyam]]\n\n| title3  = Ali Baba Mil Gaye Chalis Choron Se\n| extra3  = [[Runa Laila]], [[Aadesh]]\n\n| title4  = Ganpati Apne Gaon Chale\n| extra4  = [[Sudesh Bhosle]], [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]], [[Anupama Deshpande]]\n}}\n\nThe film featured great background music, but songs were rather not exciting{{POV statement|date=April 2020}}. Rather unusually, for a [[Bollywood]] film of the time, a West African track was used in the film. [[Guinean]] singer [[Mory Kant\u00e9's]] hit [[Y\u00e9 k\u00e9 y\u00e9 k\u00e9]] appears in the film, but is not on the soundtrack. The lyrics were penned by [[Anand Bakshi]].\n\n==Awards==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1990\n| [[Amitabh Bachchan]]\n| [[National Film Award for Best Actor]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Mithun Chakraborty]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Rohini Hattangadi]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress]]\n| {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Remake==\n{{main|Agneepath (2012 film)}}\nIn an interview with The Times of India, [[Karan Johar]] explained that he had the intention of remaking the original Agneepath ever since the film released 22 years ago, because according to him, the failure of the film broke his father's heart.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-26/news-interviews/30663491_1_agneepath-karan-johar-kancha-cheena | work=The Times of India | title=Agneepath broke my father's heart: Karan Johar | date=26 January 2012 | access-date=14 April 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023164409/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-26/news-interviews/30663491_1_agneepath-karan-johar-kancha-cheena | archive-date=23 October 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> The idea of the remake materialised on the sets of Johar's film ''[[My Name Is Khan]]'' in which Karan Malhotra was an associate director. Johar told Malhotra his desire to remake the original film and asked him to revisit it again, to which he agreed immediately.\n\nHrithik Roshan played the lead role of Vijay Deenanath Chauhan and Sanjay Dutt plays the role of the antagonist Kancha Cheena.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2010/nov/281110-Agneepath-remake-Sanjay-Dutt-Karan-Johar.htm |title=Sanjay Dutt is the bad man now |work=MidDay |access-date=15 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617084139/http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2010/nov/281110-Agneepath-remake-Sanjay-Dutt-Karan-Johar.htm |archive-date=17 June 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Priyanka Chopra was the female lead. The character of Krishnan Iyer played by Mithun Chakraborty in the original was removed and Rishi Kapoor played a newly introduced negative character, Rauf Lala.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/article/30/2011010620110106022045461abd4a9fe/Rishi-to-do-a-%E2%80%98looks-test%E2%80%99-for-Agneepath.html |title=Rishi to do a 'looks test' for Agneepath |work=Mumbai Mirror |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110109013448/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/article/30/2011010620110106022045461abd4a9fe/Rishi-to-do-a-%E2%80%98looks-test%E2%80%99-for-Agneepath.html |archivedate=9 January 2011 }}</ref> Other members of the cast include Om Puri and Zarina Wahab<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianage.com/bollywood/zarina-star-agneepath-remake-782 |title=Zarina to star in Agneepath remake |work=Asianage |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113035328/http://www.asianage.com/bollywood/zarina-star-agneepath-remake-782 |archivedate=13 January 2011 }}</ref> among others.\n\nShooting of the film mostly took place in Diu and Mumbai's film city. Originally slated for release on 20 January, ''Agneepath'' was postponed by a week to 26 January 2012. Unlike the original, the remake opened to positive responses from critics and the audience. ''[[Agneepath (2012 film)|Agneepath]]'' collected Rs 217.5&nbsp;million (US$4.34 million) on the opening day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3968&nCat= |title=Box Office 2012|work=Box Office India |access-date=14 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419165202/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3968&nCat= |archive-date=19 April 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to review aggregator Review Gang, professional critics have given the film a rating of 6.5 stars out of 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewgang.com/movies/208-Agneepath-Review |title=Agneepath review |work=Reviewgang |accessdate=14 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413140643/http://www.reviewgang.com/movies/208-Agneepath-Review |archivedate=13 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> The film did fantastic business at the box office and entered the 100 crore club.\n\nThe film was also modified and remade in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as [[Sivasakthi]], starring [[Sathyaraj]] and [[Prabhu Ganesan]] directed by [[Suresh Krissna]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|URL=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219234905/http://www3.dharma-production.com:80/FMovie/FMovieDetails.aspx?movieid=8bc11b19-2a31-4b2d-b1b3-0428da32d2e8|Agneepath (Path of Fire)}}\n* {{IMDb title|0098999|Agneepath}}\n\n{{Dharma Productions}}\n\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about organised crime in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actor National Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mukul S. Anand]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Maharashtra Police]]\n[[Category:Hindi films remade in other languages]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Madhavi\u2192Madhavi (actress),Shammi\u2192Shammi (actress),Pradeep Rawat\u2192Pradeep Rawat (actor)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agneepath_(1990_film)"}
{"title_page": "Kalakai Sanctuary", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{No footnotes|date=April 2020}}{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''Kalakai Sanctuary''' is an ancient observatory, located on a small [[plateau]] in the Biyen River valley of the [[Dzungarian Alatau|Dzungar Alatau]].\n\n=== Description ===\nThe Kalakai Shrine is composed of boulders of various sizes in the formation of a circle which measures {{Convert|100|meter|yard|abbr=}} in diameter. In the centre is a large boulder that has remained there since the collapse of a large glacier. Within the circle several large stones are constructed to resemble a large sundial, pointing in the four [[Cardinal_direction|cardinal directions]]. The monument dates back to the first millennium BC. Remains from the [[Saka]] have been found near the sanctuary, though they do not belong to the shrine.\n\nScientists have theorised that the sanctuary was designed as a clock and calendar. That is why it is referred to as The Observatory. In ancient times the shrine could be used to calculate the sunrise, the sunset, the [[Equinox|equinoxes]], the arrival of new seasons, rainy seasons, etc.\n\nThe boulder in the centre of the shrine is covered with drawings dating back to the period of the [[Saka]]. The boulder features drawings of [[Argali]] with curved horns (the symbol of the sun) as well as sacrificial holes.\n\n=== References ===\n# [https://www.drive2.ru/b/460556559768922026/ \u0421\u0432\u044f\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0439] \u2014 DRIVE2. www.drive2.ru (5 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f 2016). \u0414\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 26 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430 2019.\n# [https://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D0%94%D0%B6%D1%83%D0%BD%D0%B3%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8%D0%B9_%D0%90%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%B0%D1%83 \u0414\u0436\u0443\u043d\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0443]\n\n\n\n[[Category:Geography of Kazakhstan]]\n\n\n{{Kazakhstan-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}The '''Kalakai sanctuary''' is an ancient observatory, located on a small [[plateau]] in the Biyen River valley of the [[Dzungarian Alatau|Dzungar Alatau]].\n\n=== Description ===\nThe Kalakai Shrine is composed of small to large boulders in the formation of a circle measuring 100-meter diameter. In the centre is a large boulder that has remained there since the collapse of a large glacier. Within the circle, a construction of large stones is orientated to face the [[Cardinal_direction|cardinal directions]] resembling a large sundial. The monument dates back to the first millennium BC. Remains from the [[Saka]] period are found near the sanctuary, though they do not belong to the shrine.\n\nScientists have theorised that the design of the sanctuary is a clock and calendar. That is why it is referred to as the Observatory. In ancient times, the sunrise, the sunset, the [[Equinox|equinoxes]], the arrival of new seasons, rainy seasons, etc. were calculated using this shrine.\n\nThe boulder in the centre of the shrine is covered with drawings dating back to the [[Saka]] period. The boulder features drawings of [[Argali]] with curved horns (the symbol of the sun) as well as sacrificial holes.\n\n=== References ===\n# [https://www.drive2.ru/b/460556559768922026/ \u0421\u0432\u044f\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0439] \u2014 DRIVE2. www.drive2.ru (5 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f 2016). \u0414\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 26 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430 2019.\n# [https://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D0%94%D0%B6%D1%83%D0%BD%D0%B3%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8%D0%B9_%D0%90%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%B0%D1%83 \u0414\u0436\u0443\u043d\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0443]\n\n\n\n[[Category:Geography of Kazakhstan]]\n", "name_user": "TJScalzo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eKalakai Sanctuary:Edited for grammar and style. Attempted to clarify references to theSakabut the lack ofinline citationsmade it difficult. Marked page as a stub and added citation templates.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalakai_Sanctuary"}
{"title_page": "Trachysida mutabilis", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of beetle}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Trachysida mutabilis 2.jpg\n| genus = Trachysida\n| species = mutabilis\n| authority = (Newman, 1841)\n| synonyms = {{Species list\n|  Trachysida laetifia | (Provancher, 1877)\n|  Trachysida luridipennis | (Haldeman, 1847)\n|  Trachysida quadricollis | (LeConte, 1850)\n}}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=itis/>\n}}\n\n'''''Trachysida mutabilis''''' is a species of flower longhorn in the [[beetle]] family [[Cerambycidae]]. It is found in North America.<ref name=itis/><ref name=gbif/><ref name=buglink/><ref name=Bezark/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=itis>\n{{Cite web| title=''Trachysida mutabilis'' Report\n| url=https://www.itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=703350\n| website=Integrated Taxonomic Information System\n| accessdate=2019-09-24\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=gbif>\n{{Cite web| title=''Trachysida mutabilis''\n| url=https://www.gbif.org/species/1145165\n| website=GBIF\n| accessdate=2019-09-24\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=buglink>\n{{Cite web| title=''Trachysida mutabilis'' species Information\n| url=https://bugguide.net/node/view/35674\n| website=BugGuide.net\n| accessdate=2019-09-24\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bezark>\n{{Cite web\n| accessdate = 2019-07-02\n| title = A Photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the New World\n| last1 = Bezark | first1 = Larry G.\n| url = https://apps2.cdfa.ca.gov/publicApps/plant/bycidDB/wdefault.asp\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite report\n| title = Checklist of the Oxypeltidae, Vesperidae, Disteniidae and Cerambycidae (Coleoptera) of the Western Hemisphere\n| date = 2016\n| last1 = Bezark | first1 = L. G.\n| last2 = Monn\u00e9 | first2 = M. A.\n| url = https://apps2.cdfa.ca.gov/publicApps/plant/bycidDB/checklists/WestHemiCerambycidae2016.pdf\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n| title = Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera, Volume 6: Chrysomeloidea\n| date = 2013\n| edit