{"title_page": "U.S. State Fuel Octane Standards", "text_new": "{{original research|date=April 2019}}\nMost states do  not mandate certain standard gasoline grade [[octane rating]]s.  In the United States and Canada, octane ratings are in [[Anti-Knock Index|AKI]], commonly shown as \"(R+M)/2\". All states require gas pumps to be labeled with the correct octane level and nearly all states do regular testing to make sure gas stations are in compliance. A minimum 82 octane fuel is recommended for most vehicles produced since 1984. Older cars with [[carburetors]] could operate with lower octane fuel at higher elevations. Regardless of legality fuel with an octane rating of less than 82 is generally not offered for sale in most states. However 85 and 86 octane gasoline can still commonly be found in several [[rocky mountain]] states.\n\n== State Octane Ratings ==\nThe octane ratings below are the lowest allowed by law and may or may not reflect the actual levels offered for sale at most gas stations. [[Ethanol fuel|Ethanol]]'s effect on octane is not considered--these are ratings that are seen at the pump.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!State \n!Regular Unleaded\n!Mid-Grade Unleaded\n!Premium Unleaded\n!Notes\n|-\n| [[Alabama]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 93\n|\n|-\n| [[Alaska]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 90\n|\n|-\n| [[Arizona]]\n|87\n|89\n|91\n|\n|-\n| [[Arkansas]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 93\n|\n|-\n| [[California]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 91\n|\n|-\n| [[Colorado]]\n| 85\n| 87\n| 91\n|\n|-\n| [[Connecticut]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 93\n| 86 octane may be sold if labeled as economy<ref>http://www.ct.gov/dcp/lib/dcp/pdf/laws_and_regulations/motor_fuel_quality_regs_current_12042008_(2).pdf</ref>\n|-\n| [[Delaware]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| [[Florida]]\n| 87<ref>Florida Administrative Code 5F-2</ref>\n| 89\n| 93\n|\n|-\n| [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| 87 <ref>http://agr.georgia.gov/1fuel-measures-faqs.aspx</ref>\n| 89\n| 93 <ref>http://agr.georgia.gov/1fuel-measures-faqs.aspx</ref>\n|\n|-\n| [[Hawaii]]\n|87\n|89\n|92\n|\n|-\n| [[Idaho]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| [[Illinois]]\n|87 <ref>http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/ilcs3.asp?ActID=2339</ref>\n|89\n|91\n|93 is available at Shell and some other gas stations in Illinois.\n|-\n| [[Indiana]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 93\n|  \n|-\n| [[Iowa]]\n| 87\n| 91\n| 93\n| \n|-\n| [[Kansas]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 91\n|  \n|-\n| [[Kentucky]]\n|86<ref>http://www.lrc.state.ky.us/kar/302/079/010.htm</ref>\n|89 \n|91\n|  \n|-\n| [[Louisiana]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n|[[Maine]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 91\n| 93 (exclusively available where Shell V-Power Premium unleaded gas is sold) \n|-\n| [[Maryland]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 93\n| \n|-\n| [[Massachusetts]]\n| 87\n| 89\n| 93\n|  \n|-\n| [[Michigan]]\n| 87 \n| 89\n| 93\n| 85 and 86 octane may be sold if labeled as subregular<ref>https://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(kvnx05fhsdtufphvy1a1ste3))/documents/mcl/pdf/mcl-Act-44-of-1984.pdf</ref>\n|-\n| [[Minnesota]]\n| <88 <ref>https://www.revisor.leg.state.mn.us/statutes/?id=239.752</ref>\n| 88 \n| 91 \n| \n|-\n| [[Mississippi]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Missouri]]\n| \n| \n|  \n| \n|-\n| [[Montana]]\n| 85.5<ref>http://bsd.dli.mt.gov/weights-and-measures/faq</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Nebraska]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Nevada]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[New Hampshire]]\n| \n| \n| \n|  \n|-\n| [[New Jersey]]\n| \n| \n| \n| New Jersey checks for fraudulent labeling of octane ratings.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Jersey Weights and Measures|url=http://www.nj.gov/dep/enforcement/docs/weightsandmeasures.pdf|accessdate=7 September 2017|publisher=NJ Department of Law and Public Safety}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[New Mexico]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|87<ref>http://law.justia.com/codes/new-york/2012/agm/article-16/192-a</ref>\n|89 \n|93 \n|93 is widely available.  \n|-\n| [[North Carolina]]\n|87\n|89\n|93\n|91 octane is commonly sold as \"premium\" in the western, mountainous part of the state. \n|-\n| [[North Dakota]]\n| 87 <ref>http://www.legis.nd.gov/information/acdata/pdf/33-34-01.pdf</ref>\n|