{"title_page": "Isabel dos Santos", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Isabel Santos}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Isabel dos Santos\n| image              = \u00a9NC IdS.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Isabel dos Santos in 2019\n| birth_name         = Isabel dos Santos\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1973|4|20|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web |first=Filipe S. |last=Fernandes |url=http://multimedia.fnac.pt/multimedia/PT/pdf/9789897412257.pdf |archivedate=15 June 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615084218/http://multimedia.fnac.pt/multimedia/PT/pdf/9789897412257.pdf |title=Isabel dos Santos - Segredos e poder do dinheiro |language=pt }}</ref>\n| birth_place        = {{nowrap|[[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic|Azerbaijan SSR]], [[Soviet Union]]}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200123-in-the-spotlight-isabel-dos-santos-angola-s-princess|title=In the spotlight: Isabel dos Santos, Angola's 'princess'|website=France24}}</ref>\n| nationality        = Russia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://expresso.pt/economia/2020-01-03-Isabel-dos-Santos-muda-se-para-o-Dubai-um-novo-paraiso-fiscal|title=Isabel dos Santos muda-se para o Dubai, um novo para\u00edso fiscal|website=Jornal Expresso}}</ref> Angola\n| alma_mater         = [[King's College London]]\n| occupation         = Businesswoman\n| known_for          = \n| spouse             = {{Marriage|[[Sindika Dokolo]]|2002}}\n| children           = 3<ref name=Burgis29Mar>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/6ffd2edc-955e-11e2-a4fa-00144feabdc0.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Isabel dos Santos|work=Financial Times|first=Tom|last=Burgis|date=29 March 2013|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n| parents            = {{ubl|[[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]]|Tatiana Kukanova}}\n| website            = [https://www.isabeldossantos.com/ www.isabeldossantos.com]\n| networth           = US$2.1 billion (October 2019)<ref name=\"Forbes profile\">{{cite web |title=Forbes profile: Isabel dos Santos |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/isabel-dos-santos/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Isabel dos Santos''' (born 20 April 1973) is an [[Angola]]n businesswoman, Africa's richest woman and the eldest child of Angola's former President [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]], who ruled the country from 1979 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/portugal-dominated-angola-for-centuries-now-the-roles-are-reversed-1.3200881|title=Portugal dominated Angola for centuries. Now the roles are reversed|work=The Irish Times}}</ref><ref>[https://blogs.forbes.com/mfonobongnsehe/2011/05/02/africas-richest-women/ Forbes: Africa\u2019s Richest Women] 2 May 2011</ref> In 2013, according to ''[[Forbes]]'', her net worth had exceeded US$2 billion making her Africa's first female US dollar billionaire.<ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/> ''Forbes'' described how dos Santos acquired her wealth by taking stakes in companies doing business in Angola, suggesting that her wealth comes almost entirely from her family's power and connections.<ref name=DolanForbes>{{cite news|work=Forbes|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2013/08/14/how-isabel-dos-santos-took-the-short-route-to-become-africas-richest-woman/|title=Daddy's Girl: How An African 'Princess' Banked $3 Billion in a Country Living On $2 Per Day|first=Kerry A. |last=Dolan|date=14 August 2013|accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/isabel-dos-santos-desmente-acusacoes-de-enriquecimento-ilicito-feitas-pela-forbes_175473.html|title=Isabel dos Santos desmente acusa\u00e7\u00f5es de enriquecimento il\u00edcito feitas pela Forbes|work=Econ\u00f3mico}}</ref> In November 2015, the [[BBC]] named dos Santos as one of the 100 most influential women in the world.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-34745739 BBC 100 Women 2015: Who is on the list?] BBC, 17 November 2015</ref>\n\nThe Angolan Government has, since 2018, been trying to prosecute Isabel dos Santos for past corruption crimes that may have led to Angola's ongoing recession crisis. However, she remains in exile in Portugal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.angonoticias.com/Artigos/item/62572/gestao-da-sonangol-pgr-mandou-instaurar-processo-criminal-contra-isabel-dos-santos|title=Gest\u00e3o da Sonangol: PGR mandou instaurar processo criminal contra Isabel dos Santos|website=ANGONOT\u00cdCIAS|access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref> On 30 December 2019, the [[Luanda Provincial Court]] ordered the freezing of dos Santos's Angolan bank accounts and the seizure of her stake in local companies, including [[Unitel (Angola)|Unitel]] and {{ill|Banco de Fomento Angola|de}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-50956370|title=Angola orders Isabel dos Santos asset seizure|date=31 December 2019|publisher=BBC}}</ref> In the meantime, she is under investigation in Portugal and has since assumed the UAE as her official country of residence.<ref name=\"JEcon\u00f3mico\">{{cite news|url=https://jornaleconomico.sapo.pt/noticias/exclusivo-dciap-investiga-operacoes-de-isabel-dos-santos-denunciadas-por-ana-gomes-534043|title=Exclusivo. DCIAP investiga opera\u00e7\u00f5es de Isabel dos Santos denunciadas por Ana Gomes|first=L\u00edgia|last=Sim\u00f5es|publisher=Jornal Econ\u00f3mico|date=10 January 2020|language=pt|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DW\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/pt-002/angola-cidad%C3%A3-russa-isabel-dos-santos-imune-%C3%A0-extradi%C3%A7%C3%A3o/a-51932233|title=Angola: Cidad\u00e3 russa Isabel dos Santos imune \u00e0 extradi\u00e7\u00e3o?|publisher=DeutscheWelle|language=pt|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"RFI\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20200111-portugal-justice-ouvre-enquete-isabel-dos-santos-angola|title=Portugal: la justice ouvre une enqu\u00eate sur Isabel dos Santos|language=fr|date=11 January 2020|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref> Two weeks later, the Angolan Government announced it was preparing the legal battle for the confiscation of dos Santos's assets in Portugal,<ref>{{cite news |URL=https://www.angola24horas.com/index.php/angola-24-horas-noticias/item/15706-governo-angolano-prepara-confisco-de-bens-de-isabel-dos-santos-em-portugal|title=Governo angolano prepara confisco de bens de Isabel dos Santos em Portugal|publisher=Angola24horas|language=pt|date=11 January 2020|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref> a process that is already in operation in the form of [[letters rogatory]] sent to Portugal to stop the transfer of funds from [[Portuguese Commercial Bank]] to a Russian bank.{{which|date=January 2020}}<ref name=\"JEcon\u00f3mico2\">{{cite news|url=https://jornaleconomico.sapo.pt/noticias/de-bestial-a-persona-non-grata-531049|title=De bestial a persona non-grata|first=V\u00edtor|last=Norinha|publisher=Jornal Econ\u00f3mico|date=3 January 2020|language=pt|accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Family and education ==\nIsabel dos Santos was born in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic|Azerbaijan SSR]],<ref name=\"auto\">[http://multimedia.fnac.pt/multimedia/PT/pdf/9789897412257.pdf ISABEL DOS SANTOS - SEGREDOS E PODER DO DINHEIRO] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615084218/http://multimedia.fnac.pt/multimedia/PT/pdf/9789897412257.pdf |date=15 June 2016 }}. Filipe S. Fernandes. Documentation (Portuguese)</ref> the oldest daughter of Angola's former President [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]] and his first wife, the Russian-born Tatiana Kukanova, whom he met while studying in the then [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] republic of [[Azerbaijan]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/25/isobel-dos-santos-africas-first-female-billionaire The Guardian: \"Isabel dos Santos, dubbed 'princess', named Africa's first female billionaire\" by David Smith] 25 January 2013</ref><ref>[http://mg.co.za/article/2012-11-02-00-angola-whos-who-in-the-palace Mail & Guardian (Zambia): \"Angola: Who's who in the palace?\" by Louise Redvers] 2 November 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/angolan-africas-first-woman-billionaire/story-fn3dxix6-1226561407045 The Australian: \"Angolan Africa's first woman billionaire\"] 25 January 2013</ref> Her father's parents came from [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]].<ref name=MPLA>[http://mpla-angola.org/opresidente.php#bio Biography at MPLA website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122000811/http://www.mpla-angola.org/opresidente.php |date=22 January 2011 }} {{in lang|pt}}</ref><ref>[http://mg.co.za/article/2012-11-02-00-angola-whos-who-in-the-palace Mail & Guardian: \"Angola: Who's who in the palace?\" by Louise Redvers] 2 November 2012</ref> She attended the all girls boarding school in Kent, [[Cobham Hall School]]. She studied [[electrical engineering]]<ref>Celso Filipe, [https://www.jornaldenegocios.pt/home.php?template=SHOWNEWS_V2&id=345996 Report about Isabel dos Santos on Neg\u00f3cios Online], December 2008</ref> at [[King's College London|King's College]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21184854|title=Isabel dos Santos: 'First African female billionaire'|publisher=BBC News|date=25 January 2013}}</ref> There she met her husband from [[Zaire]] (now [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]), [[Sindika Dokolo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dokolo.com/Sa%20famille.html|title=La Famille Dokolo : Ndona Tuluka - Nzolantima - Hanne - Manzanza - Sindika - Luzolo}}</ref> a son of a millionaire from [[Kinshasa]] and his [[Denmark|Danish]] wife.<ref>{{cite web|title=Augustin Dokolo, an African entrepreneur|url=http://www.dokolo.com/Biography.html|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:\u00a9NC IdS080.jpg|thumb|left|Isabel dos Santos in 2014]]\nIn the past 20 years dos Santos has held management positions in a number of companies listed on European stock exchanges. Dos Santos returned from [[London]] in the early 1990s to join her father in [[Luanda]] and started working as a project manager engineer for ''Urbana 2000'', a subsidiary of Jembas Group, that had won a contract to clean and disinfect the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publico.pt/economia/noticia/isabel-dos-santos-o-rosto-de-angola-1300051|title=Isabel dos Santos: o rosto de Angola|language=Portuguese|date=20 July 2007|work=P\u00fablico|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> Following that, she set up a trucking business. The widespread use of walkie-talkie technology paved the way for her subsequent foray into telecoms.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/6ffd2edc-955e-11e2-a4fa-00144feabdc0.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Isabel dos Santos|work=Financial Times}}</ref> In 1997, she started her first business, opening the ''Miami Beach Club'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theafricaneconomist.com/meet-the-forbes-second-richest-african-woman-isabel-dos-santos/|title=Meet The Forbes Second Richest African Woman: Isabel dos Santos|date=4 December 2012|work=The African Economist|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> one of the first night clubs and beach restaurants on the [[Ilha de Luanda|Luanda Island]]. Over nearly 20 years she expanded her business interests, leading to the creation of several holdings, in Angola and mostly abroad, making substantial investments in high-profile entreprises, especially in Portugal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/isabel-dos-santos-reforca-em-portugal-com-entrada-na-zon_77174.html |title=Isabel dos Santos refor\u00e7a em Portugal com entrada na Zon Di\u00e1rio Econ\u00f3mico, 21 December 2009 (pt) |access-date=28 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315062549/http://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/isabel-dos-santos-reforca-em-portugal-com-entrada-na-zon_77174.html |archive-date=15 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[https://www.jornaldenegocios.pt/negocios-iniciativas/poderosos/detalhe/isabel_dos_santos_eacute_a_18ordf_figura_mais_poderosa_da_economia_portuguesa Isabel dos Santos \u00e9 a 18\u00aa figura mais poderosa da economia portuguesa Jornal de Neg\u00f3cios, 4 August 2011 (pt)]</ref> In June 2016, she was appointed by her father as chairwoman of [[Sonangol Group|Sonangol]], the Angolan state oil company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mgafrica.com/article/2016-06-03-all-in-the-family-angola-president-picks-eldest-daughter-to-head-state-oil-firm-western-firms-scramble-for-contract|title=All in the family: Angola president picks eldest daughter to head state oil firm, western firms scramble for contracts|date=3 June 2016|work=MG Africa|access-date=14 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216103334/http://mgafrica.com/article/2016-06-03-all-in-the-family-angola-president-picks-eldest-daughter-to-head-state-oil-firm-western-firms-scramble-for-contract|archive-date=16 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The controversial appointment in the wake of similar appointments of children of the president to key posts was short-lived, as Jo\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o, the new Angolan President, fired her merely two months after being sworn into office.<ref>See e.g. Novo Jornal / Luanda, 10 March 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-angola-sonangol/angola-president-dismisses-sonangol-chair-isabel-dos-santos-idUSKBN1DF1X5 by Reuters]</ref>\n\nOn 30 December 2019, the Luanda Provincial Court ordered the preventive seizure of personal bank accounts of dos Santos, her husband, Sindika Dokolo, and M\u00e1rio Filipe Moreira Leite da Silva. According to the Attorney General's Office, the three businesspeople entered into deals with the Angolan state through the companies Sodiam, a public diamond sales company, and Sonangol, the state oil company. With these deals, the Angolan state suffered a loss of $1.14 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabado.pt/mundo/detalhe/tribunal-decreta-arresto-preventivo-a-contas-e-empresas-de-isabel-dos-santos|title=Tribunal decreta arresto preventivo a contas e empresas de Isabel dos Santos|website=sabado.pt}}</ref> The court produced a document showing that the assets and many others owned by dos Santos had been acquired using funds from two state-owned companies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=469e48c0-3483-11ea-88f8-31dc410bb4c0&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMS0wMy9hZnJpY2Etcy1yaWNoZXN0LXdvbWFuLXNheXMtYXNzZXQtZnJlZXplLWRvb21zLWhlci1hbmdvbGFuLWZpcm1z|title=Bloomberg Are you a robot?|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref> In the meantime, the Portuguese Attorney-General's Office has revealed that an investigation has been opened into a number of operations by Isabel dos Santos, following a charge laid by [[Ana Gomes]], a Portuguese [[Member of the European Parliament]].<ref name=\"JEcon\u00f3mico\"/> Following the seizure, she has assumed the [[UAE]] as her official country of residence.<ref name=\"DW\"/><ref name=\"RFI\"/>\n\n=== Investments in Portugal ===\n[[File:\u00a9Nuno Coimbra IdS.jpg|thumb|right|Isabel dos Santos in 2017]]\nSince 2008 she has had interests in [[telecommunications]], [[Mass media|media]], [[retail]], [[finance]] and the [[energy industry]], both in Angola and in [[Portugal]]. In addition to her commercial interest in oil and diamonds, dos Santos also owns shares in the Angola cement company [[Nova Cimangola]]. Jadeium, a company held by dos Santos, acquired 4.918% of ZON Multimedia shares from Spain's [[Telefonica]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/PQ39531.pdf |title=Qualified Shareholding |date=8 May 2012 |work=CMVM }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/PQ39584.pdf |title=Qualified Shareholding |date=9 May 2012 |work=CMVM }}</ref>\n\nThrough the [[Netherlands]]-based ''Unitel International Holdings BV'',<ref name=\"ANNOUNCEMENT\">{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/FR42703.pdf |title=ANNOUNCEMENT |work=CMVM Official website |date=14 December 2012 }}</ref> a company controlled by dos Santos,<ref>[http://www.portugaldailyview.com/whats-new/isabel-dos-santos-reinforces-her-presence-in-portuguese-firms Angola: Isabel dos Santos reinforces her presence in Portuguese firms] ''Portugaldailyview.com'', 9 May 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.millenniumbcp.pt/multimedia/archive/00422/ZON_422000a.pdf Millennium investment banking: Kento qualified holding comment] 14 March 2011 (page 1)</ref> the Angolan businesswoman is the main shareholder of [[ZON Multim\u00e9dia]] with 29% since July 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euronext.com/trader/companyprofile/companyprofilev2-18661-EN-PTZON0AM0006.html?selectedMep=5|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710205425/http://www.euronext.com/trader/companyprofile/companyprofilev2-18661-EN-PTZON0AM0006.html?selectedMep=5|url-status=dead|title=NYSE Euronext Company profile|archivedate=10 July 2011}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110809060709/http://economia.publico.pt/Noticia/accionistas-da-zon-aprovam-por-unanimidade-entrada-de-isabel-dos-santos_1420467 Zon's shareholders unanimously approved the entry of Isabel dos Santos (pt)]</ref> She is member of the board of Angolan bank in Lisbon, {{ill|Banco BIC Portugu\u00eas|pt|EuroBic}},<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bancobic.pt/Conteudos/Artigos/detalhe.aspx?idc=361&idl=1 |title=BIC board members |access-date=26 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521015351/http://www.bancobic.pt/Conteudos/Artigos/detalhe.aspx?idc=361&idl=1 |archive-date=21 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and through ''Santoro Holding'' she holds 20% stakes at [[Banco Portugu\u00eas de Investimento]].<ref>[http://bpi.bancobpi.pt/index.asp?riIdArea=AreaAccionistas&riId=AAccionista Shareholders structure BPI 24 June 2011 (pt)]</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-22/dos-santos-to-request-permission-to-raise-stake-in-bpi-negocios.html Bloomberg: Isabel dos Santos wants to raise stake at BPI, 22 December 2010]</ref> She has other major stakes with the Angolan state oil company [[Sonangol]] through their mutual European Law holding, based in the Netherlands, named ''Esperanza Holding'', in Portuguese [[Galp Energia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.voanews.com/portuguese/news/02_03_angolaportugaloil_voanews-115196319.html |title=Report on Voice of America (pt) |access-date=15 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522160502/http://www.voanews.com/portuguese/news/02_03_angolaportugaloil_voanews-115196319.html |archive-date=22 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Dos Santos is a founding member and Board member of Banco BIC Portugu\u00eas,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bancobic.pt/eportal/v10/PT/aspx/oBpn/governo/modelogov/index.aspx |title=Banco BIC Portugu\u00eas Official website |access-date=12 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121216011142/http://www.bancobic.pt/eportal/v10/PT/aspx/oBpn/governo/modelogov/index.aspx |archive-date=16 December 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which recently acquired [[Wikipedia:Banco_Portugu%C3%AAs_de_Neg%C3%B3cios|Banco Portugu\u00eas de Neg\u00f3cios]], a nationalized bank.<ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/>\n\n[[File:\u00a9Nuno Coimbra143.jpg|thumb|right|Isabel dos Santos in 2018]]\nSince November 2012 dos Santos is a non-executive board member of ZON.<ref>[http://www.ionline.pt/dinheiro/isabel-dos-santos-integra-administracao-da-zon ''Isabel dos Santos integra administra\u00e7\u00e3o da [[NOS (Portuguese media company)|Zon]] by LUSA Press agency''] ionline.pt. Retrieved 7 July 2018 (portugueses)</ref> In December 2012, dos Santos announced the invitation for a merger of ZON with Sonaecom, proved in March 2013 by the General Assembly.<ref name=\"ANNOUNCEMENT\"/> Eight months later, after the green light from the Competition Authority, the merger of the two companies was formalized on 27 August 2013, with the transfer to ZOPT, a special purpose vehicle created to advance the operation which became the owner of more 50% of the capital of the new group, the shares that dos Santos and Sonaecom hold on Zon and Optimus respectively. There was a capital increase of ZOPT through contribution in kind from 50 to 716 million euros, while Sonaecom subscribed 358 million shares of the company, by delivering 81.8% of its stake in Optimus. The Angolan businesswoman, on her turn, subscribed exactly the same number of shares of ZOPT, through her holdings Kento and [[Unitel (Angola)|Unitel]] International, delivering 28.8% of the stake in ZON.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/PQ46594.pdf |title=Qualified Shareholding |work=CMVM }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/ODRA46598.pdf |title=Announcement |date=28 August 2013 |work=CMVM }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/TRAN46596.pdf |title=Manager Transactions |work=CMVM }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/ODRA46592.pdf |title=Announcement |work=CMVM }}</ref> With this transfer of shareholdings in Optimus and Zon, Sonaecom and dos Santos became holders of over 50% stake in the merged company: Zon Optimus SGPS. On this occasion, a new strategy for the company was announced by dos Santos, with a multimarket vision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portugaleconomyprobe.pt/library/we-suggest/news-a-facts/8289-press-review-merger-of-zon-multimedia-and-optimus-approved-in-portugal-great-potential-for-expansion|title=Optimus, Zon merger brings potential for expansion - Dos Santos|access-date=30 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021155811/http://www.portugaleconomyprobe.pt/library/we-suggest/news-a-facts/8289-press-review-merger-of-zon-multimedia-and-optimus-approved-in-portugal-great-potential-for-expansion|archive-date=21 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibra.pt/empresas/6779-zonoptimus-merger-isabel-dos-santos-the-strategy-of-the-new-company-will-be-open-to-new-geographies.html|title=Isabel dos Santos The strategy of the new company will be open to new geographies|access-date=30 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021164628/http://www.fibra.pt/empresas/6779-zonoptimus-merger-isabel-dos-santos-the-strategy-of-the-new-company-will-be-open-to-new-geographies.html|archive-date=21 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 1 October 2013, Isabel dos Santos attended the first General Assembly of Zon Optimus.<ref>[https://www.sabado.pt/ultima-hora/detalhe/Isabel-dos-Santos-comparece-na-AG-da-Zon-Optimus ''Isabel dos Santos comparece na AG da Zon Optimus''] sabado.pt. Retrieved 7 July 2018 (portuguese)</ref> Isabel dos Santos' investments in Portugal are in listed companies, which are therefore subject to official supervision of the Portuguese Securities Market Commission (CMVM).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmvm.pt/en/a%20cmvm/apresentacao/pages/apresentacao.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=12 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130331031857/http://www.cmvm.pt/en/a%20cmvm/apresentacao/pages/apresentacao.aspx |archivedate=31 March 2013 }} CMVM</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, dos Santos launched a takeover bid for [[Portugal Telecom]], SGPS, S.A., valuing the firm's shares at \u20ac1.35 a share, in what was seen as a rival bid to a previous \u20ac7 billion offer from [[Altice (company)|Altice]]. Though the offer made by Altice is on PT Portugal, not on PT SGPS.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/09/us-portugal-nos-pt-idUSKCN0IT0T520141109 NOS shareholder bids for Portugal Telecom shares] Reuters, 9 November 2014</ref> On 1 December 2014, the Angolan businesswoman formally registered her offer at the [[Portuguese Securities Market Commission]] (Comiss\u00e3o do Mercado de Valores Mobili\u00e1rios, CMVM, in Portuguese).<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/01/portugal-telecom-santos-idUSL6N0TI42Q20141201 Dos Santos launches bid for Portugal Telecom SGPS] Reuters, 1 December 2014</ref>\n\nIn January 2017 [[Unitel (Angola)|Unitel]], led by dos Santos, officialized the purchase of 2% of Banco Fomento de Angola (BFA) from BPI for 28 million euros and now controls 51.9% of the bank's capital.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=10946343 BFA Announces Board Changes] Bloomberg, January 2017</ref> The operation was approved by sector regulators, namely the [[National Bank of Angola]] (BNA) in December 2016. In February 2017 dos Santos decides to sell her position in Banco BPI, following the takeover bid launched by [[CaixaBank]]. Dos Santos arrived in 2009, stepped out{{clarify|date=January 2020}} in 2017 and won more than 80 million euros: Santos' capital gain comes not only from the sale of the 18.5% holding on BPI, but also from the dividends from 2008 and 2009, worth around 12.6 million euros.<ref>[http://econews.pt/2017/02/14/isabel-dos-santos-steps-out-of-bpi-with-80-million Isabel dos Santos steps out of BPI with 80 million] ECO News, 14 February 2017</ref>\n\n=== Investments in Angola ===\nWith 51% control of ''Condis'', dos Santos signed a joint partnership with the Portuguese [[Sonae]] group in April 2011 for the development and operation of a retail trading company in Angola. The entry in Angola by the Portuguese group led by [[Paulo de Azevedo]] will be performed by the [[Modelo Continente|Continente (Angola)]], which plans to open the first supermarket by 2013 in Angola.<ref>[http://www.portugalglobal.pt/PT/PortugalNews/Paginas/NewDetail.aspx?newId=%7BE0DA500A-CE60-4924-ADA7-8FAEE6AB3411%7D Portuguese group Sonae authorised to open hypermarkets in Angola] Aicep Portugal Global. Retrieved 27 December 2011</ref>\n\n=== Focus on telecommunications ===\n[[File:\u00a9NC IdS199.jpg|thumb|right|Isabel dos Santos in 2019]]\nShe created [[Unitel (Angola)|Unitel]] in partnership with [[Portugal Telecom]], after a tender process she considered fair.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Also through Unitel International Holding, a platform for Unitel investments where Portugal Telecom has no presence, she acquired the mobile operator T+, in Cape Verde and gained the license for the establishment of the second telecom operator in S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portalangop.co.ao/motix/pt_pt/noticias/ciencia-e-tecnologia/2013/2/13/Unitel-Internacional-assina-contrato-para-ser-segunda-operadora-Sao-Tome-Principe,1f36edd7-2279-4dc4-a9ed-fe5b29bf157c.html|title=Unitel Internacional assina contrato para ser segunda operadora em S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 e Pr\u00edncipe|work=ANGOP}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/unitel-takes-over-control-of-t-in-cape-verde--903089|title=Unitel takes over control of T+ in Cape Verde}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africatelecomit.com/unitel-to-become-second-operator-in-sao-tome-principe/|title=Africa Telecom & IT \u2013 Unitel to become second operator in Sao Tome & Principe}}</ref> Under this investment dos Santos announced during a visit to S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe that Unitel will invest in education in the country to train engineers, managers and other technicians and also focus on job creation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macauhub.com.mo/en/2013/05/31/unitel-stp-to-start-operating-in-sao-tome-and-principe-this-year|title=Unitel STP to start operating in Sao Tome and Principe this year|work=Macauhub English|date=30 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nBy 2015, dos Santos owned a share of satellite-TV operator ZAP, that had in December 2013 acquired the rights to distribute ''Forbes'' in a number of Portuguese speaking countries, namely Portugal, Angola and Mozambique. It had been announced that most of the content would be produced by a local team, complemented by content for the North American edition, therefore potentially allowing influence on ''Forbes'' content. It was initially planned that the first edition of the Portuguese language ''Forbes'' would be published during the second quarter of 2014.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publico.pt/economia/noticia/forbes-chega-este-ano-a-portugal-e-africa-pela-mao-de-isabel-dos-santos-1699597|title=Forbes chega este ano a Portugal e \u00c1frica, pela m\u00e3o de Isabel dos Santos|author=P\u00daBLICO|work=P\u00daBLICO}}</ref>\n\n=== Holdings ===\nHoldings of dos Santos in the recent years:<ref>[http://www.dinheirovivo.pt/Mercados/Artigo/CIECO045020.html?page=2 Os neg\u00f3cios de Isabel dos Santos em Portugal] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222200703/http://www.dinheirovivo.pt/Mercados/Artigo/CIECO045020.html?page=2 |date=22 February 2014 |work=Dinheiro Vivo Online|accessdate= 9 May 2012 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>[http://www.clipquick.com/Files/Imprensa/2012/08-01/0/1_1870377_7E1C4A2D8B3731959B5EFFAA1CAC6C0A.pdf A Angolana mais rica de Portugal, English: ''The most rich Angolan in Portugal'' clipquick.com, 1 August 2012 (pt)]</ref>\n\n* Trans Africa Investment Services, a [[Gibraltar]] based vehicle founded together with her mother for the diamond business\n* Unitel International Holdings B.V.: change of name of Kento and Jadeium, based in [[Amsterdam]], company-vehicle for dos Santos' investment in telecommunications\n* Santoro Finance: company-vehicle for dos Santos' investment in Banco BPI based in [[Lisbon]]\n* Esperaza Holding B.V.: based in [[Amsterdam]], energy, oil etc.\n* Condis: a retail business based in Luanda\n\n== ''Luanda Leaks'' ==\nOn 19 January 2020 the [[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]] (ICIJ) published a detailed report on how dos Santos amassed her wealth over the years. The report \u2013 which it called ''Luanda Leaks'' \u2013 provides evidence of how she \"made a fortune at the expense of the Angolan people\".<ref>[https://www.icij.org/investigations/luanda-leaks/ ''Isabel dos Santos made a fortune at the expense of the Angolan people, Luanda Leaks reveals.''] icij.org, published 19 January 2020</ref>\n\nThe night of 22 January, just days after the leaks, her personal wealth manager and private banking director Nuno Ribeiro da Cunha was found dead in the garage of his house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elconfidencial.com/mundo/2020-01-23/luanda-leaks-aparece-muerto-gestor-financiero-isabel-dos-santos_2424912/|title=Luanda Leaks {{!}} Aparece muerto en Portugal el gestor financiero de Isabel dos Santos|date=23 January 2020|website=El Confidencial|language=es|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* {{official|https://www.isabeldossantos.com/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santos, Isabel dos}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Angolan businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Baku]]\n[[Category:Children of national leaders]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Female billionaires]]\n[[Category:Angolan Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Angolan people of S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe descent]]\n[[Category:Angolan people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Angolan billionaires]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriates in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:21st-century Angolan people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Angolan people]]\n[[Category:21st-century businesswomen]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Isabel Santos}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Isabel dos Santos\n| image              = \u00a9NC IdS.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Isabel dos Santos in 2019\n| birth_name         = Isabel dos Santos\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1973|4|20|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web |first=Filipe S. |last=Fernandes |url=http://multimedia.fnac.pt/multimedia/PT/pdf/9789897412257.pdf |archivedate=15 June 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615084218/http://multimedia.fnac.pt/multimedia/PT/pdf/9789897412257.pdf |title=Isabel dos Santos - Segredos e poder do dinheiro |language=pt }}</ref>\n| birth_place        = {{nowrap|[[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic|Azerbaijan SSR]], [[Soviet Union]]}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200123-in-the-spotlight-isabel-dos-santos-angola-s-princess|title=In the spotlight: Isabel dos Santos, Angola's 'princess'|website=France24}}</ref>\n| nationality        = Russia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://expresso.pt/economia/2020-01-03-Isabel-dos-Santos-muda-se-para-o-Dubai-um-novo-paraiso-fiscal|title=Isabel dos Santos muda-se para o Dubai, um novo para\u00edso fiscal|website=Jornal Expresso}}</ref> Angola\n| alma_mater         = [[King's College London]]\n| occupation         = Businesswoman\n| known_for          = \n| spouse             = {{Marriage|[[Sindika Dokolo]]|2002}}\n| children           = 3<ref name=Burgis29Mar>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/6ffd2edc-955e-11e2-a4fa-00144feabdc0.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Isabel dos Santos|work=Financial Times|first=Tom|last=Burgis|date=29 March 2013|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n| parents            = {{ubl|[[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]]|Tatiana Kukanova}}\n| website            = [https://www.isabeldossantos.com/ www.isabeldossantos.com]\n| networth           = US$2.1 billion (October 2019)<ref name=\"Forbes profile\">{{cite web |title=Forbes profile: Isabel dos Santos |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/isabel-dos-santos/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Isabel dos Santos''' (born 20 April 1973) is an [[Angola]]n businesswoman, Africa's richest woman and the eldest child of Angola's former President [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]], who ruled the country from 1979 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/portugal-dominated-angola-for-centuries-now-the-roles-are-reversed-1.3200881|title=Portugal dominated Angola for centuries. Now the roles are reversed|work=The Irish Times}}</ref><ref>[https://blogs.forbes.com/mfonobongnsehe/2011/05/02/africas-richest-women/ Forbes: Africa\u2019s Richest Women] 2 May 2011</ref> In 2013, according to ''[[Forbes]]'', her net worth had exceeded US$2 billion making her Africa's first female US dollar billionaire.<ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/> ''Forbes'' described how dos Santos acquired her wealth by taking stakes in companies doing business in Angola, suggesting that her wealth comes almost entirely from her family's power and connections.<ref name=DolanForbes>{{cite news|work=Forbes|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2013/08/14/how-isabel-dos-santos-took-the-short-route-to-become-africas-richest-woman/|title=Daddy's Girl: How An African 'Princess' Banked $3 Billion in a Country Living On $2 Per Day|first=Kerry A. |last=Dolan|date=14 August 2013|accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/isabel-dos-santos-desmente-acusacoes-de-enriquecimento-ilicito-feitas-pela-forbes_175473.html|title=Isabel dos Santos desmente acusa\u00e7\u00f5es de enriquecimento il\u00edcito feitas pela Forbes|work=Econ\u00f3mico}}</ref> In November 2015, the [[BBC]] named dos Santos as one of the 100 most influential women in the world.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-34745739 BBC 100 Women 2015: Who is on the list?] BBC, 17 November 2015</ref>\n\nThe Angolan Government has, since 2018, been trying to prosecute Isabel dos Santos for past corruption crimes that may have led to Angola's ongoing recession crisis. However, she remains in exile in Portugal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.angonoticias.com/Artigos/item/62572/gestao-da-sonangol-pgr-mandou-instaurar-processo-criminal-contra-isabel-dos-santos|title=Gest\u00e3o da Sonangol: PGR mandou instaurar processo criminal contra Isabel dos Santos|website=ANGONOT\u00cdCIAS|access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref> On 30 December 2019, the [[Luanda Provincial Court]] ordered the freezing of dos Santos's Angolan bank accounts and the seizure of her stake in local companies, including [[Unitel (Angola)|Unitel]] and {{ill|Banco de Fomento Angola|de}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-50956370|title=Angola orders Isabel dos Santos asset seizure|date=31 December 2019|publisher=BBC}}</ref> In the meantime, she is under investigation in Portugal and has since assumed the UAE as her official country of residence.<ref name=\"JEcon\u00f3mico\">{{cite news|url=https://jornaleconomico.sapo.pt/noticias/exclusivo-dciap-investiga-operacoes-de-isabel-dos-santos-denunciadas-por-ana-gomes-534043|title=Exclusivo. DCIAP investiga opera\u00e7\u00f5es de Isabel dos Santos denunciadas por Ana Gomes|first=L\u00edgia|last=Sim\u00f5es|publisher=Jornal Econ\u00f3mico|date=10 January 2020|language=pt|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DW\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/pt-002/angola-cidad%C3%A3-russa-isabel-dos-santos-imune-%C3%A0-extradi%C3%A7%C3%A3o/a-51932233|title=Angola: Cidad\u00e3 russa Isabel dos Santos imune \u00e0 extradi\u00e7\u00e3o?|publisher=DeutscheWelle|language=pt|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"RFI\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20200111-portugal-justice-ouvre-enquete-isabel-dos-santos-angola|title=Portugal: la justice ouvre une enqu\u00eate sur Isabel dos Santos|language=fr|date=11 January 2020|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref> Two weeks later, the Angolan Government announced it was preparing the legal battle for the confiscation of dos Santos's assets in Portugal,<ref>{{cite news |URL=https://www.angola24horas.com/index.php/angola-24-horas-noticias/item/15706-governo-angolano-prepara-confisco-de-bens-de-isabel-dos-santos-em-portugal|title=Governo angolano prepara confisco de bens de Isabel dos Santos em Portugal|publisher=Angola24horas|language=pt|date=11 January 2020|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref> a process that is already in operation in the form of [[letters rogatory]] sent to Portugal to stop the transfer of funds from [[Portuguese Commercial Bank]] to a Russian bank.{{which|date=January 2020}}<ref name=\"JEcon\u00f3mico2\">{{cite news|url=https://jornaleconomico.sapo.pt/noticias/de-bestial-a-persona-non-grata-531049|title=De bestial a persona non-grata|first=V\u00edtor|last=Norinha|publisher=Jornal Econ\u00f3mico|date=3 January 2020|language=pt|accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Family and education ==\nIsabel dos Santos was born in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic|Azerbaijan SSR]],<ref name=\"auto\">[http://multimedia.fnac.pt/multimedia/PT/pdf/9789897412257.pdf ISABEL DOS SANTOS - SEGREDOS E PODER DO DINHEIRO] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615084218/http://multimedia.fnac.pt/multimedia/PT/pdf/9789897412257.pdf |date=15 June 2016 }}. Filipe S. Fernandes. Documentation (Portuguese)</ref> the oldest daughter of Angola's former President [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]] and his first wife, the Russian-born Tatiana Kukanova, whom he met while studying in the then [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] republic of [[Azerbaijan]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/25/isobel-dos-santos-africas-first-female-billionaire The Guardian: \"Isabel dos Santos, dubbed 'princess', named Africa's first female billionaire\" by David Smith] 25 January 2013</ref><ref>[http://mg.co.za/article/2012-11-02-00-angola-whos-who-in-the-palace Mail & Guardian (Zambia): \"Angola: Who's who in the palace?\" by Louise Redvers] 2 November 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/angolan-africas-first-woman-billionaire/story-fn3dxix6-1226561407045 The Australian: \"Angolan Africa's first woman billionaire\"] 25 January 2013</ref> Her father's parents came from [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]].<ref name=MPLA>[http://mpla-angola.org/opresidente.php#bio Biography at MPLA website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122000811/http://www.mpla-angola.org/opresidente.php |date=22 January 2011 }} {{in lang|pt}}</ref><ref>[http://mg.co.za/article/2012-11-02-00-angola-whos-who-in-the-palace Mail & Guardian: \"Angola: Who's who in the palace?\" by Louise Redvers] 2 November 2012</ref> She attended the all girls boarding school in Kent, [[Cobham Hall School]]. She studied [[electrical engineering]]<ref>Celso Filipe, [https://www.jornaldenegocios.pt/home.php?template=SHOWNEWS_V2&id=345996 Report about Isabel dos Santos on Neg\u00f3cios Online], December 2008</ref> at [[King's College London|King's College]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21184854|title=Isabel dos Santos: 'First African female billionaire'|publisher=BBC News|date=25 January 2013}}</ref> There she met her husband from [[Zaire]] (now [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]), [[Sindika Dokolo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dokolo.com/Sa%20famille.html|title=La Famille Dokolo : Ndona Tuluka - Nzolantima - Hanne - Manzanza - Sindika - Luzolo}}</ref> a son of a millionaire from [[Kinshasa]] and his [[Denmark|Danish]] wife.<ref>{{cite web|title=Augustin Dokolo, an African entrepreneur|url=http://www.dokolo.com/Biography.html|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:\u00a9NC IdS080.jpg|thumb|left|Isabel dos Santos in 2014]]\nIn the past 20 years dos Santos has held management positions in a number of companies listed on European stock exchanges. Dos Santos returned from [[London]] in the early 1990s to join her father in [[Luanda]] and started working as a project manager engineer for ''Urbana 2000'', a subsidiary of Jembas Group, that had won a contract to clean and disinfect the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publico.pt/economia/noticia/isabel-dos-santos-o-rosto-de-angola-1300051|title=Isabel dos Santos: o rosto de Angola|language=Portuguese|date=20 July 2007|work=P\u00fablico|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> Following that, she set up a trucking business. The widespread use of walkie-talkie technology paved the way for her subsequent foray into telecoms.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/6ffd2edc-955e-11e2-a4fa-00144feabdc0.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Isabel dos Santos|work=Financial Times}}</ref> In 1997, she started her first business, opening the ''Miami Beach Club'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theafricaneconomist.com/meet-the-forbes-second-richest-african-woman-isabel-dos-santos/|title=Meet The Forbes Second Richest African Woman: Isabel dos Santos|date=4 December 2012|work=The African Economist|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> one of the first night clubs and beach restaurants on the [[Ilha de Luanda|Luanda Island]]. Over nearly 20 years she expanded her business interests, leading to the creation of several holdings, in Angola and mostly abroad, making substantial investments in high-profile entreprises, especially in Portugal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/isabel-dos-santos-reforca-em-portugal-com-entrada-na-zon_77174.html |title=Isabel dos Santos refor\u00e7a em Portugal com entrada na Zon Di\u00e1rio Econ\u00f3mico, 21 December 2009 (pt) |access-date=28 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315062549/http://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/isabel-dos-santos-reforca-em-portugal-com-entrada-na-zon_77174.html |archive-date=15 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[https://www.jornaldenegocios.pt/negocios-iniciativas/poderosos/detalhe/isabel_dos_santos_eacute_a_18ordf_figura_mais_poderosa_da_economia_portuguesa Isabel dos Santos \u00e9 a 18\u00aa figura mais poderosa da economia portuguesa Jornal de Neg\u00f3cios, 4 August 2011 (pt)]</ref> In June 2016, she was appointed by her father as chairwoman of [[Sonangol Group|Sonangol]], the Angolan state oil company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mgafrica.com/article/2016-06-03-all-in-the-family-angola-president-picks-eldest-daughter-to-head-state-oil-firm-western-firms-scramble-for-contract|title=All in the family: Angola president picks eldest daughter to head state oil firm, western firms scramble for contracts|date=3 June 2016|work=MG Africa|access-date=14 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216103334/http://mgafrica.com/article/2016-06-03-all-in-the-family-angola-president-picks-eldest-daughter-to-head-state-oil-firm-western-firms-scramble-for-contract|archive-date=16 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The controversial appointment in the wake of similar appointments of children of the president to key posts was short-lived, as Jo\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o, the new Angolan President, fired her merely two months after being sworn into office.<ref>See e.g. Novo Jornal / Luanda, 10 March 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-angola-sonangol/angola-president-dismisses-sonangol-chair-isabel-dos-santos-idUSKBN1DF1X5 by Reuters]</ref>\n\nOn 30 December 2019, the Luanda Provincial Court ordered the preventive seizure of personal bank accounts of dos Santos, her husband, Sindika Dokolo, and M\u00e1rio Filipe Moreira Leite da Silva. According to the Attorney General's Office, the three businesspeople entered into deals with the Angolan state through the companies Sodiam, a public diamond sales company, and Sonangol, the state oil company. With these deals, the Angolan state suffered a loss of $1.14 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabado.pt/mundo/detalhe/tribunal-decreta-arresto-preventivo-a-contas-e-empresas-de-isabel-dos-santos|title=Tribunal decreta arresto preventivo a contas e empresas de Isabel dos Santos|website=sabado.pt}}</ref> The court produced a document showing that the assets and many others owned by dos Santos had been acquired using funds from two state-owned companies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=469e48c0-3483-11ea-88f8-31dc410bb4c0&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMS0wMy9hZnJpY2Etcy1yaWNoZXN0LXdvbWFuLXNheXMtYXNzZXQtZnJlZXplLWRvb21zLWhlci1hbmdvbGFuLWZpcm1z|title=Bloomberg Are you a robot?|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref> In the meantime, the Portuguese Attorney-General's Office has revealed that an investigation has been opened into a number of operations by Isabel dos Santos, following a charge laid by [[Ana Gomes]], a Portuguese [[Member of the European Parliament]].<ref name=\"JEcon\u00f3mico\"/> Following the seizure, she has assumed the [[UAE]] as her official country of residence.<ref name=\"DW\"/><ref name=\"RFI\"/>\n\n=== Investments in Portugal ===\n[[File:\u00a9Nuno Coimbra IdS.jpg|thumb|right|Isabel dos Santos in 2017]]\nSince 2008 she has had interests in [[telecommunications]], [[Mass media|media]], [[retail]], [[finance]] and the [[energy industry]], both in Angola and in [[Portugal]]. In addition to her commercial interest in oil and diamonds, dos Santos also owns shares in the Angola cement company [[Nova Cimangola]]. Jadeium, a company held by dos Santos, acquired 4.918% of ZON Multimedia shares from Spain's [[Telefonica]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/PQ39531.pdf |title=Qualified Shareholding |date=8 May 2012 |work=CMVM }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/PQ39584.pdf |title=Qualified Shareholding |date=9 May 2012 |work=CMVM }}</ref>\n\nThrough the [[Netherlands]]-based ''Unitel International Holdings BV'',<ref name=\"ANNOUNCEMENT\">{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/FR42703.pdf |title=ANNOUNCEMENT |work=CMVM Official website |date=14 December 2012 }}</ref> a company controlled by dos Santos,<ref>[http://www.portugaldailyview.com/whats-new/isabel-dos-santos-reinforces-her-presence-in-portuguese-firms Angola: Isabel dos Santos reinforces her presence in Portuguese firms] ''Portugaldailyview.com'', 9 May 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.millenniumbcp.pt/multimedia/archive/00422/ZON_422000a.pdf Millennium investment banking: Kento qualified holding comment] 14 March 2011 (page 1)</ref> the Angolan businesswoman is the main shareholder of [[ZON Multim\u00e9dia]] with 29% since July 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euronext.com/trader/companyprofile/companyprofilev2-18661-EN-PTZON0AM0006.html?selectedMep=5|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710205425/http://www.euronext.com/trader/companyprofile/companyprofilev2-18661-EN-PTZON0AM0006.html?selectedMep=5|url-status=dead|title=NYSE Euronext Company profile|archivedate=10 July 2011}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110809060709/http://economia.publico.pt/Noticia/accionistas-da-zon-aprovam-por-unanimidade-entrada-de-isabel-dos-santos_1420467 Zon's shareholders unanimously approved the entry of Isabel dos Santos (pt)]</ref> She is member of the board of Angolan bank in Lisbon, {{ill|Banco BIC Portugu\u00eas|pt|EuroBic}},<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bancobic.pt/Conteudos/Artigos/detalhe.aspx?idc=361&idl=1 |title=BIC board members |access-date=26 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521015351/http://www.bancobic.pt/Conteudos/Artigos/detalhe.aspx?idc=361&idl=1 |archive-date=21 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and through ''Santoro Holding'' she holds 20% stakes at [[Banco Portugu\u00eas de Investimento]].<ref>[http://bpi.bancobpi.pt/index.asp?riIdArea=AreaAccionistas&riId=AAccionista Shareholders structure BPI 24 June 2011 (pt)]</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-22/dos-santos-to-request-permission-to-raise-stake-in-bpi-negocios.html Bloomberg: Isabel dos Santos wants to raise stake at BPI, 22 December 2010]</ref> She has other major stakes with the Angolan state oil company [[Sonangol]] through their mutual European Law holding, based in the Netherlands, named ''Esperanza Holding'', in Portuguese [[Galp Energia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.voanews.com/portuguese/news/02_03_angolaportugaloil_voanews-115196319.html |title=Report on Voice of America (pt) |access-date=15 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522160502/http://www.voanews.com/portuguese/news/02_03_angolaportugaloil_voanews-115196319.html |archive-date=22 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Dos Santos is a founding member and Board member of Banco BIC Portugu\u00eas,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bancobic.pt/eportal/v10/PT/aspx/oBpn/governo/modelogov/index.aspx |title=Banco BIC Portugu\u00eas Official website |access-date=12 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121216011142/http://www.bancobic.pt/eportal/v10/PT/aspx/oBpn/governo/modelogov/index.aspx |archive-date=16 December 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which recently acquired Banco Portugu\u00eas de Neg\u00f3cios, a nationalized bank.<ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/>\n\n[[File:\u00a9Nuno Coimbra143.jpg|thumb|right|Isabel dos Santos in 2018]]\nSince November 2012 dos Santos is a non-executive board member of ZON.<ref>[http://www.ionline.pt/dinheiro/isabel-dos-santos-integra-administracao-da-zon ''Isabel dos Santos integra administra\u00e7\u00e3o da [[NOS (Portuguese media company)|Zon]] by LUSA Press agency''] ionline.pt. Retrieved 7 July 2018 (portugueses)</ref> In December 2012, dos Santos announced the invitation for a merger of ZON with Sonaecom, proved in March 2013 by the General Assembly.<ref name=\"ANNOUNCEMENT\"/> Eight months later, after the green light from the Competition Authority, the merger of the two companies was formalized on 27 August 2013, with the transfer to ZOPT, a special purpose vehicle created to advance the operation which became the owner of more 50% of the capital of the new group, the shares that dos Santos and Sonaecom hold on Zon and Optimus respectively. There was a capital increase of ZOPT through contribution in kind from 50 to 716 million euros, while Sonaecom subscribed 358 million shares of the company, by delivering 81.8% of its stake in Optimus. The Angolan businesswoman, on her turn, subscribed exactly the same number of shares of ZOPT, through her holdings Kento and [[Unitel (Angola)|Unitel]] International, delivering 28.8% of the stake in ZON.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/PQ46594.pdf |title=Qualified Shareholding |work=CMVM }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/ODRA46598.pdf |title=Announcement |date=28 August 2013 |work=CMVM }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/TRAN46596.pdf |title=Manager Transactions |work=CMVM }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi2004/emitentes/docs/ODRA46592.pdf |title=Announcement |work=CMVM }}</ref> With this transfer of shareholdings in Optimus and Zon, Sonaecom and dos Santos became holders of over 50% stake in the merged company: Zon Optimus SGPS. On this occasion, a new strategy for the company was announced by dos Santos, with a multimarket vision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portugaleconomyprobe.pt/library/we-suggest/news-a-facts/8289-press-review-merger-of-zon-multimedia-and-optimus-approved-in-portugal-great-potential-for-expansion|title=Optimus, Zon merger brings potential for expansion - Dos Santos|access-date=30 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021155811/http://www.portugaleconomyprobe.pt/library/we-suggest/news-a-facts/8289-press-review-merger-of-zon-multimedia-and-optimus-approved-in-portugal-great-potential-for-expansion|archive-date=21 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibra.pt/empresas/6779-zonoptimus-merger-isabel-dos-santos-the-strategy-of-the-new-company-will-be-open-to-new-geographies.html|title=Isabel dos Santos The strategy of the new company will be open to new geographies|access-date=30 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021164628/http://www.fibra.pt/empresas/6779-zonoptimus-merger-isabel-dos-santos-the-strategy-of-the-new-company-will-be-open-to-new-geographies.html|archive-date=21 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 1 October 2013, Isabel dos Santos attended the first General Assembly of Zon Optimus.<ref>[https://www.sabado.pt/ultima-hora/detalhe/Isabel-dos-Santos-comparece-na-AG-da-Zon-Optimus ''Isabel dos Santos comparece na AG da Zon Optimus''] sabado.pt. Retrieved 7 July 2018 (portuguese)</ref> Isabel dos Santos' investments in Portugal are in listed companies, which are therefore subject to official supervision of the Portuguese Securities Market Commission (CMVM).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmvm.pt/en/a%20cmvm/apresentacao/pages/apresentacao.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=12 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130331031857/http://www.cmvm.pt/en/a%20cmvm/apresentacao/pages/apresentacao.aspx |archivedate=31 March 2013 }} CMVM</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, dos Santos launched a takeover bid for [[Portugal Telecom]], SGPS, S.A., valuing the firm's shares at \u20ac1.35 a share, in what was seen as a rival bid to a previous \u20ac7 billion offer from [[Altice (company)|Altice]]. Though the offer made by Altice is on PT Portugal, not on PT SGPS.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/09/us-portugal-nos-pt-idUSKCN0IT0T520141109 NOS shareholder bids for Portugal Telecom shares] Reuters, 9 November 2014</ref> On 1 December 2014, the Angolan businesswoman formally registered her offer at the [[Portuguese Securities Market Commission]] (Comiss\u00e3o do Mercado de Valores Mobili\u00e1rios, CMVM, in Portuguese).<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/01/portugal-telecom-santos-idUSL6N0TI42Q20141201 Dos Santos launches bid for Portugal Telecom SGPS] Reuters, 1 December 2014</ref>\n\nIn January 2017 [[Unitel (Angola)|Unitel]], led by dos Santos, officialized the purchase of 2% of Banco Fomento de Angola (BFA) from BPI for 28 million euros and now controls 51.9% of the bank's capital.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=10946343 BFA Announces Board Changes] Bloomberg, January 2017</ref> The operation was approved by sector regulators, namely the [[National Bank of Angola]] (BNA) in December 2016. In February 2017 dos Santos decides to sell her position in Banco BPI, following the takeover bid launched by [[CaixaBank]]. Dos Santos arrived in 2009, stepped out{{clarify|date=January 2020}} in 2017 and won more than 80 million euros: Santos' capital gain comes not only from the sale of the 18.5% holding on BPI, but also from the dividends from 2008 and 2009, worth around 12.6 million euros.<ref>[http://econews.pt/2017/02/14/isabel-dos-santos-steps-out-of-bpi-with-80-million Isabel dos Santos steps out of BPI with 80 million] ECO News, 14 February 2017</ref>\n\n=== Investments in Angola ===\nWith 51% control of ''Condis'', dos Santos signed a joint partnership with the Portuguese [[Sonae]] group in April 2011 for the development and operation of a retail trading company in Angola. The entry in Angola by the Portuguese group led by [[Paulo de Azevedo]] will be performed by the [[Modelo Continente|Continente (Angola)]], which plans to open the first supermarket by 2013 in Angola.<ref>[http://www.portugalglobal.pt/PT/PortugalNews/Paginas/NewDetail.aspx?newId=%7BE0DA500A-CE60-4924-ADA7-8FAEE6AB3411%7D Portuguese group Sonae authorised to open hypermarkets in Angola] Aicep Portugal Global. Retrieved 27 December 2011</ref>\n\n=== Focus on telecommunications ===\n[[File:\u00a9NC IdS199.jpg|thumb|right|Isabel dos Santos in 2019]]\nShe created [[Unitel (Angola)|Unitel]] in partnership with [[Portugal Telecom]], after a tender process she considered fair.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Also through Unitel International Holding, a platform for Unitel investments where Portugal Telecom has no presence, she acquired the mobile operator T+, in Cape Verde and gained the license for the establishment of the second telecom operator in S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portalangop.co.ao/motix/pt_pt/noticias/ciencia-e-tecnologia/2013/2/13/Unitel-Internacional-assina-contrato-para-ser-segunda-operadora-Sao-Tome-Principe,1f36edd7-2279-4dc4-a9ed-fe5b29bf157c.html|title=Unitel Internacional assina contrato para ser segunda operadora em S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 e Pr\u00edncipe|work=ANGOP}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/unitel-takes-over-control-of-t-in-cape-verde--903089|title=Unitel takes over control of T+ in Cape Verde}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africatelecomit.com/unitel-to-become-second-operator-in-sao-tome-principe/|title=Africa Telecom & IT \u2013 Unitel to become second operator in Sao Tome & Principe}}</ref> Under this investment dos Santos announced during a visit to S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe that Unitel will invest in education in the country to train engineers, managers and other technicians and also focus on job creation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macauhub.com.mo/en/2013/05/31/unitel-stp-to-start-operating-in-sao-tome-and-principe-this-year|title=Unitel STP to start operating in Sao Tome and Principe this year|work=Macauhub English|date=30 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nBy 2015, dos Santos owned a share of satellite-TV operator ZAP, that had in December 2013 acquired the rights to distribute ''Forbes'' in a number of Portuguese speaking countries, namely Portugal, Angola and Mozambique. It had been announced that most of the content would be produced by a local team, complemented by content for the North American edition, therefore potentially allowing influence on ''Forbes'' content. It was initially planned that the first edition of the Portuguese language ''Forbes'' would be published during the second quarter of 2014.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publico.pt/economia/noticia/forbes-chega-este-ano-a-portugal-e-africa-pela-mao-de-isabel-dos-santos-1699597|title=Forbes chega este ano a Portugal e \u00c1frica, pela m\u00e3o de Isabel dos Santos|author=P\u00daBLICO|work=P\u00daBLICO}}</ref>\n\n=== Holdings ===\nHoldings of dos Santos in the recent years:<ref>[http://www.dinheirovivo.pt/Mercados/Artigo/CIECO045020.html?page=2 Os neg\u00f3cios de Isabel dos Santos em Portugal] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222200703/http://www.dinheirovivo.pt/Mercados/Artigo/CIECO045020.html?page=2 |date=22 February 2014 |work=Dinheiro Vivo Online|accessdate= 9 May 2012 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>[http://www.clipquick.com/Files/Imprensa/2012/08-01/0/1_1870377_7E1C4A2D8B3731959B5EFFAA1CAC6C0A.pdf A Angolana mais rica de Portugal, English: ''The most rich Angolan in Portugal'' clipquick.com, 1 August 2012 (pt)]</ref>\n\n* Trans Africa Investment Services, a [[Gibraltar]] based vehicle founded together with her mother for the diamond business\n* Unitel International Holdings B.V.: change of name of Kento and Jadeium, based in [[Amsterdam]], company-vehicle for dos Santos' investment in telecommunications\n* Santoro Finance: company-vehicle for dos Santos' investment in Banco BPI based in [[Lisbon]]\n* Esperaza Holding B.V.: based in [[Amsterdam]], energy, oil etc.\n* Condis: a retail business based in Luanda\n\n== ''Luanda Leaks'' ==\nOn 19 January 2020 the [[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]] (ICIJ) published a detailed report on how dos Santos amassed her wealth over the years. The report \u2013 which it called ''Luanda Leaks'' \u2013 provides evidence of how she \"made a fortune at the expense of the Angolan people\".<ref>[https://www.icij.org/investigations/luanda-leaks/ ''Isabel dos Santos made a fortune at the expense of the Angolan people, Luanda Leaks reveals.''] icij.org, published 19 January 2020</ref>\n\nThe night of 22 January, just days after the leaks, her personal wealth manager and private banking director Nuno Ribeiro da Cunha was found dead in the garage of his house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elconfidencial.com/mundo/2020-01-23/luanda-leaks-aparece-muerto-gestor-financiero-isabel-dos-santos_2424912/|title=Luanda Leaks {{!}} Aparece muerto en Portugal el gestor financiero de Isabel dos Santos|date=23 January 2020|website=El Confidencial|language=es|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* {{official|https://www.isabeldossantos.com/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santos, Isabel dos}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Angolan businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Baku]]\n[[Category:Children of national leaders]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Female billionaires]]\n[[Category:Angolan Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Angolan people of S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe descent]]\n[[Category:Angolan people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Angolan billionaires]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriates in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:21st-century Angolan people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Angolan people]]\n[[Category:21st-century businesswomen]]\n", "name_user": "Josemrsantos", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isabel_dos_Santos"}
{"title_page": "2020 Challenge Tour", "text_new": "The '''2020 Challenge Tour''' is a series of professional [[golf]] tournaments collectively known as the [[Challenge Tour]].\n\nThe Challenge Tour is Europe's official developmental [[professional golf tours|tour]] and is organised by the [[PGA European Tour]]. It was introduced in 1986 and was originally called the Satellite Tour, before being renamed with its present title in 1990.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.europeantour.com/tourgroup/history/index.html |title=Tour History |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] |accessdate=16 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722071906/http://www.europeantour.com/tourgroup/history/index.html |archivedate=22 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Tournament schedule==\nThe 2020 schedule is set out below.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/challenge-tour/schedule/2020/ |title=Challenge Tour Schedule 2020 |publisher=[[PGA European Tour]] |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> The numbers in brackets after winners' names show the player's total number of wins on the Challenge Tour including that event. It is rare for someone to accumulate many wins on the Challenge Tour because success at this level soon leads to promotion to the [[European Tour]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Dates!!Tournament!!Host country!!Winner!![[Official World Golf Ranking|OWGR]]<br>points!!Purse (\u20ac)!!Notes\n|-\n| 2 Feb || [[Limpopo Championship]] || [[South Africa]] || {{flagicon|ZAF}} [[J. C. Ritchie]] (1) || align=center|13 || align=right|$250,000 || Co-sanctioned with the [[Sunshine Tour]]\n|-\n| 9 Feb || [[RAM Cape Town Open]] || [[South Africa]] || {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Anton Karlsson (golfer)|Anton Karlsson]] (1) || align=center|13 || align=right|$250,000 || Co-sanctioned with the [[Sunshine Tour]]\n|-\n| 16 Feb || [[Dimension Data Pro-Am]] || [[South Africa]] || {{flagicon|ZAF}} [[Christiaan Bezuidenhout]] (n/a) || align=center|13 