{"title_page": "Christopher Charles Benninger", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name = Christopher Charles Benninger\n| image = Christopher Charles Benninger.JPG\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1942|11|23}}\n| birth_place = Hamilton, Ohio, USA\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = American-Indian\n| alma_mater  = [[Harvard Graduate School of Design|Harvard GSD]]<br />[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]\n| awards = Great Master Architect of India\n| practice = CCBA Designs\n| significant_buildings = Mahindra United World College, Suzlon One Earth, India House\n| significant_projects = [[Royal Supreme Court, Bhutan]]; College of Engineering Pune, Indian Institute of Technology, Hyderabad\n}}\n[[Image:Suzlon One Earth Headquarters, Pune, India. Photo A. Ramprasad (10).jpg|thumb|[[Suzlon One Earth]], designed by Christopher Benninger, in [[Pune]], [[Maharashtra]].]]\n\n'''Christopher Charles Benninger''' is an American-Indian architect and planner..\n\n==About==\n\nChristopher Charles Benninger (b.1942) is one of India\u2019s highly decorated architects. His award-winning projects are the Mahindra United World College of India, the Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies, \u201cSuzlon One Earth\u201d world headquarters, the National Ceremonial Plaza at Thimphu, Bhutan, and his own studio and residence \u201cIndia House\u201d in Pune. Each project addresses the complex issues of design, context, climate, materials, sustainability, and technology, amidst the client\u2019s programmatic needs. Christopher studied urban planning at MIT and architecture at Harvard, where he later taught. He settled in India in 1971, founding the School of Planning at Ahmedabad as a Ford Foundation Advisor, where he continues as a Distinguished Professor. His name appears alongside Geoffrey Bawa, Charles Correa and Balkrishna Doshi as one of the six recipients of the Great Master Architect Award in India, presented every three years. \n\nHis firm, Christopher Charles Benninger Architects, has recently been awarded India\u2019s most sought after commissions: the Azim Premji University at Bengaluru; and the Indian Institute of Technology at Hyderabad, along with the Indian Institute of Management at Kolkata. His city and regional planning works range from Sri Lanka, across India to Bhutan. Benninger\u2019s expansive campuses reveal an understanding of Indian \u201cplace making\u201d, reflecting the great temple complexes and the Mogul campuses. His narrative presents a language that lies between American ideals embedded in wooded Arcadian landscapes and sacred notions enshrined within Indian courtyards, generating a unique approach to architecture and place making.\n\n==Early Life==\n\nChristopher was born in [[Hamilton, Ohio]] in 1942, in the midst of the Second World War. His father, Lawrence Joseph Benninger was then teaching soldiers how to keep the army\u2019s accounts. As the War ended, his family moved to settle down for a few years in Columbia at the University of Missouri. In 1955, they left the Mid-west, stopping in the Deep South for a year and then moving on to [[Gainesville, Florida]], where his father later retired as a Professor Emeritus at the [[University of Florida]]. His father published influential articles and textbooks on accounting, reflecting his own difficult childhood in the Great Depression.\n\nHis paternal grandfather, Ernest Eberlein was an artist settled in Free Acres, an experimental free-tax community in the Watchung Mountains west of the Hudson River.\n\nGlimpsing through the striking gardens of Gainesville inspired Christopher to himself create a new world of nature with gardens penetrating into living spaces and household activities taking place outdoors. Seeing this interest, his maternal aunt presented him with The Natural House, Frank Lloyd Wright\u2019s compelling autobiographical book setting out his credo on architecture. Reading the book, a 14-year old Christopher decided what he wanted to be- an architect. \n\n==Education==\n\n[[University of Florida]]\n\nChristopher graduated from the Department of Architecture at the University of Florida in 1966. He studied Architecture at Grove Hall, a temporary wooden barrack put up in the Second World War for officers\u2019 training. He learnt from a core group of great teachers, including Blair Reeves, Robert Tucker, Turpin C. Bannister, Norman Jensen, Bernard Voichysonk, Dan Branch and Harry C. Merritt. They opened windows for him on new thoughts, concepts and issues, and fostered great competition. Professor Merritt led him to leave the small university town of Gainesville for the city of Boston to attend Harvard.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''MIT and Harvard University''' }}\n\nChristopher completed his Master of Architecture from the Graduate School of Architecture in 1967 and him Master of City Planning from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in 1971. In Cambridge, he worked in Jose Luis Sert\u2019s studio, who was his mentor and his teacher at the GSD. Walter Gropius, though retired by then, would visit the their studios and pose questions. He interacted with the likes of Jerzy Soltan, Joseph Zalewski and Albert Szabo. He was equally inspire by the American school of thought that embraced nature, wildlife and the cycles of the seasons, and the European school of thought dominant in Cambridge at the time, that pushed architecture to float above nature and worship sky gods, abstraction and ideas. \n\n\nAt MIT, Kevin Lynch awakened his understanding of cities, places and urban experiences, while Herbert Gans encouraged him to explore the social ecology of neighbourhoods and how people used them. At Sert\u2019s studio on Church Street, he worked on the Harvard Science Center and Sert\u2019s new studio on Brattle Street- rationalist buildings that continue to inspire him even today. \n\n\nEven though he was an architect, he studied Economics under John Kenneth Gailbraith and became Barbara Ward\u2019s prot\u00e9g\u00e9, traveling with her to Greece to attend the Delos Symposium on Doxiadis\u2019 yacht. There, he was introduced to Edmund Bacon, Margaret Mead, Arnold Toynbee and Buckminster Fuller. \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Fullbright Fellowship (First visit to India)''' }}\n\nIn October 1968, Christopher travelled to India on a Fulbright Fellowship. He taught at the Ahmedabad School of Architecture as a Visiting Lecturer and researched low-income settlements in Ahmedabad. While in India, he designed a site and services housing scheme in Vadodara for the social workers Sanatbhai and Anuradhaben Mehta.\n\n==Career==\n\nProfessor Benninger, is widely regarded as one of India\u2019s foremost creative architects, and is respected as a leading urban and regional planner. He has been registered with the [[Council of Architecture]] since 1976, and is a Fellow of both the [http://www.itpi.org.in/ Institute of Town Planners], India and the [https://iigeo.org/ Indian Institute of Architects]. He is a member of the Regional Science Association, India, the [https://iigeo.org/ Institute of Indian Geographers], the [http://puneinternationalcentre.org/ Pune International Centre], the World Society of [[Ekistics]], the [[American Planning Association]], the [[American Institute of Architects]], and the [[India Habitat Centre]]. \n\nUnder Sanat Mehta\u2019s Housing Ministry in Gujarat, 1972, he designed India\u2019s first [[Economically Weaker Section]] township in [[Jamnagar]] funded by [[HUDCO]]. He designed two [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SOS_Children%27s_Villages SOS Children\u2019s Villages] (Kolkata and Bawana) in 1973 and 1975, and the Alliance Francaise in Ahmedabad in that period. In 1976 he moved to [[Pune]] where he founded the Centre for Development Studies and Activities [CDSA], whose well-known campus he designed in the mid-1980s.\n\n\nBeginning in 1976 he worked with the Hyderabad Urban Development Authority to design their first Low Income Housing Township at Yousufguda that shelters more than two thousand low-income households. From 1974 to 1978 he designed the Madras Metropolitan Development Authority\u2019s pioneering Site and Services Programme, under which more than fifteen thousand shelter units were created with the participation of owner-builders from the city\u2019s slums. Under UNO funding, 1979\u201382, he prepared the development plans for six cities in Sri Lanka. In the 1980s professor Benninger prepared Integrated Rural Development Programmes for Ratnagiri, Etawah, Goa, Almora and many other districts with the GOI, [[UNICEF]] and local district governments.\n\nUnder [[World Bank]] funding he has prepared development plans for the cities of Kalyan and Thane [1986-90] through the [[BMRDA]]; studies and recommendations for the planning of twenty-eight urban centres in Madhya Pradesh [1988-92], and other plans for Indian cities.\n\n\nWhile the Executive Director of the Centre for Development Studies and Activities he was a Member of the University Faculty Senate and on the Board of University Teaching and Research [BUTR] of the [[Pune University]]; on the Bureau of Indian Standards Expert\u2019s Group on Urban Planning, Architecture and Construction Norms and Standards; on several HUDCO policy committees, and he carried out research and the preparation of policy papers for the Planning Commission, the Ministries of Rural Development, Women and Children [preparing the Integrated District Development Programme, GOI, funded by UNICEF, Home Affairs [Tribal Development]. He has advised the World Bank, the [[Asian Development Bank]], the [[UNCHS]] [Habitat]; the [[UNFAO]], UNICEF and the [[Ford Foundation]] regarding development initiatives in India, Bhutan, Sri Lanka, Malaysia, Indonesia and other countries.\n\nAs an expert advisor to the UNCHS [Habitat] Professor Benninger wrote the Theme Paper for the Seventh United Nations Commission Meeting on Human Settlements [1983], and in 1986 he wrote the Asian Development Bank\u2019s Draft Urban Investment Policy. He was a Member of the Technology Information Forecasting and Assessment Council [TIFAC], Ministry of Science and Technology from 1988 onwards. He remains a Distinguished Professor at [[CEPT University]] in Ahmedabad and Chairman of the Board of the Centre for Development Studies and Activities, Pune and is an Honorary Trustee of the Pune International Centre. Professor Benninger served on the Bilateral Board of Directors of the United States Educational Foundation [Fulbright Foundation] in India for three terms.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD | '''Academic Career''' }} \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD | '''Harvard University''' }} \n\nIn January 1970, by the age of 27, Christopher was promoted as a tenured Assistant Professor at Harvard and was a member of the Faculty Senate.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD | '''School of Planning, CEPT''' }} \n\nIn 1971, on the invitation of Balkrishna Doshi, Christopher promptly resigned from Harvard send returned to Ahmedabad to start the School of Planning, at what is now CEPT University.  As it\u2019s Founder, Christopher developed the curriculum, hired faculty and brought in good students from all across India. \n\nThe School of Planning was an important experiment. It drew students from architecture, engineering, social work, law, the liberal arts and technology, upsetting the accreditation committees of civil engineers, geographers and architects. Their pedagogy was through \u2018laboratories,\u2019 rather than classrooms and studios. Students and teachers lived in villages, rural towns and slums \u2018learning from the people\u2019 with whom we made plans for the future. Theoretical subjects were cross-disciplinary involving administrators, social scientists, architects, community leaders and technicians.\n\nApart from being a Distinguished Professor, Christopher currently serves as a Member on the Academic Council at CEPT to help set policy on course content, faculty recruitment, research goals, and programme and faculty development.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD | '''Centre for Development Studies and Activities (CDSA)''' }}\n\nChristopher shifted to Pune to start CDSA in 1976 at the age of thirty-three. This was his second institution, a place of intellectual research and social action. At the peak of CDSA\u2019s ascendance more than eighty young professionals worked in offices at Pune, Bhutan, Goa,in the foothills of the Himalayas in Almora, and in Jaffna and Galle in Sri Lanka. They prepared town plans and slum improvement programs. They pioneered micro-watershed planning, micro-level social services planning, decentralized planning and participatory planning. \n\nHis twenty years at CDSA were spent inventing, enabling and facilitating programs, all to assist households to climb out of poverty. They worked in teams; they joined with villages and slum dwellers as their research laboratories, classrooms and teachers; and they drew from all disciplines. CDSA was part of an active network including the Indian Planning Commission, the National Housing Bank, the Housing and Urban Development Corporation and the Ministries of Social Welfare, Rural Development and Urban Affairs. Internationally, they worked with the UNCHS (Habitat) in Nairobi, the Asian Development Bank in Manila and the World Bank in Washington. Many programs in Bhutan and in India were developed with the United Nations.\n\nThe new School of Planning at CDSA was founded on didactic techniques initiated in Ahmedabad. The real world became the learning laboratory. Students lived in slums and villages learning from those they would plan for. Poverty alleviation, sustainability and equality were the main concerns and issues to be debated. Methods of \u2018stress identification\u2019, problem identification, program design and monitoring the results of development inputs were evolved. Land models, common resources models and social structure models were invented and explored. At CDSA, \u2018modern\u2019 came to mean planned and facilitated change that eradicated poverty, in a manner that employed limited resources rationally. It involved the civil society, NGOs, governments and the people.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD | '''Impact on Architectural Education in India''' }}\n\nProfessor Benninger has delivered 15 International lectures and more than 235 national lectures till date to the architecture, engineering and construction fraternities. Many of his books reached those remote corners educating students in the absence of good teachers of architecture and planning in India. Letters to a Young Architect, with its Gujarati, Bengali and Chinese translations, is a book that has crossed the language divide to reach aspiring architects and designers. His second book, Christopher Benninger: Architecture for Modern India, took Indian Modern Architecture to the world while celebrating India\u2019s age old traditions of the sustainable built environment. His contribution to the profession is not limited to giving a shape to the institutions and campuses he designed but in the evolution of his thoughts and design process.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD | '''Architecture''' }}\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''CCBA Designs: The studio''' }}\n\nCCBA Designs started as a small proprietorship design firm in 1995 by the Company Founder Chairman and Principal Architect Prof. Christopher Benninger along with Founder Managing Director Mr. Ramprasad Akkisetti. With the changing economic liberalization, and part of the expansion plan, Benninger Technical Services came into being in 1999 that eventually morphed into Christopher Charles Benninger Architects Private Limited (shortened to be addressed as CCBA) in 2000. CCBA is an Incorporated Company registered in 1999 under the Companies act 1956.\n\nThe team has always functioned as a studio, only accepting commissions involving study, analysis and the exploration of visual, spatial, social and technological concepts impinging on architecture, urbanism and human settlements. As an internationally known \u2018design house\u2019 CCBA has created products ranging from a capital city and new towns; educational campuses and corporate headquarters; housing communities and complexes; hotels and resorts; and on to the design of chairs and art works. In the end, it is not the \u201cthings\u201d they design, but the transcendental experience of the people using them, looking at them, or just being in them, which is their essence.  For the studio, the good life exists just a step outside of materiality, in a mystic twilight zone, which is called architecture.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''''India House: The Abode for Art''''' }}\n\nCCBA Designs operates from the founding directors own premises, India House.  This abode of design provides a salubrious work environment with galleries, recreational facilities and a Courtyard. The gallery is dedicated to the exhibition of master artist\u2019s work, exploring timeless energy with fresh commitment. India House Art Gallery stands for passion, dedicated to the interpretation of human existence through highly crafted imagery. The gallery is committed to working with exceptional artists who are visually gifted, technically exceptional, and of important artistic merit and accomplishment. Whatever the medium represented the art works are well rafted, unique and transformational. Though tied to no specific aesthetic philosophy, the gallery seeks to introduce the connoisseurs of Pune and the rest of India to creative genius that is of truly international quality, and influential nature. The gallery hosts autumn, winter and spring exhibitions, with related talks and seminars.\n\n==Early Works==\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''SOS Children\u2019s Villages''' }}\n\nThe SOS Children\u2019s Villages in India were an outcome of a social in Europe to care for orphans after the Second World War. The campuses in Bawana and Kolkata were the second and third such orphanages created in the sub-continent. Each village is composed of a headmaster\u2019s house, a clinic, a library, a community hall, utility buildings and twenty Houses. Each house accommodates both, children and a housemother.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''SOS Children\u2019s Village, Bawana, Haryana''' }}\n\nLocated in Bawana Village fifty kilometres from Delhi, this small campus is designed around a central village square. Narrow paths lead through four portals into four neighbourhood plazas, which in turn lead into domestic courtyards of five houses. Thus, the campus is conceived as a hierarchy of social spaces, where a child can find their own comfort level, either alone in their bedroom reading. The entire village is laid out on parallel lines, over which brick bearing walls are built and brick arched ceiling vaults span above these ground level spaces.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''SOS Children\u2019s Village, Kolkata, West Bengal''' }}\n\nThe SOS Children\u2019s Village in Kolkata emerged as a call from Mother Teresa to shelter the parentless children emerging from the freedom movement and subsequent war in Bangladesh. This village followed the same building programme, module sizes and room areas as the Bawana Village. Unlike the Bawana village, the Kolkata village is located within a dense urban fabric. An identical set of functions in an identical building programme was expressed in a completely different architectural language and spatial system.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''''Alliance Francaise, Ahmedabad, Gujarat''''' }}\n\nIn 1973 the Gujarat United School of Theology initiated the construction of a small, 260 sq. m., library and cultural centre for [https://ccba.in/project/alliance-francaise/ Alliance Francaise] that would house a specialized collection of books and a common cultural area for small programs. The structure is located in a corner site, accessible through the main academic quadrangle, of a late Nineteenth Century institution built from brick and trimmed with stone.  The strategy employs exposed brick bearing walls, reinforced for seismic resistance, and exposed concrete beams, lintels and fins transparently expressing the structural system. Natural lighting comes from north facing skylights, high in the ceilings, which wrap down the back north wall. A system of nine modules, 4.75 meters square, order the floor plan of nine such modules into a system of inter-locked, double height spaces. This module is halved to create pivoting square doors, and defined in three equal subdivisions to modulate the spacing of beams, turning down the back walls as fins, within which glass windows are fit. Modular toilets project out of this back wall. Interlocking volumes create a kinetic flow of spaces between three areas. An exposed concrete column, in the centre of the main space, creates the illusion of movement as one walks within the structure. \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Centre for Development Studies and Activities, Pune, Maharashtra''' }}\n\nThe [https://cdsaindia.org/ Centre for Development Studies and Activities] (CDSA) is a place of exploration, reflection and analysis on the great laboratory that is India. It was built by the architect for his own trust activities whose focal concerns are the study of development processes and the role of planned interventions in societal changes. [https://ccba.in/project/cdsa/ The campus] is perched on a hill terrace along the slopes of India\u2019s Western Ghats Mountains as they meet the great plains of the Deccan Plateau providing scenic vistas. A fabric of build has emerged from the assemblage of three generic elements namely which are stone, transparent sliding panels and tile roofs. An interesting play of spaces has been created with the studios opening out into their own intimate landscaped courtyards, which again visually connect to the main central podium through square apertures. This openness reveals the deep-rooted meaning of the Institute, in which the liberated mind searches for the resolution of specific problems, often through teamwork, or through the exchange of opposing ideas.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''United World College Mahindra, Mulshi, Maharashtra''' }}\n\nThe [https://ccba.in/project/uwc-mahindra-college/ Mahindra United World College] of India is one the 12 campuses worldwide under the [http://uwcmahindracollege.org/gallery United World College] banner. Patronized by the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anand_Mahindra Mahindra family], the college accommodates about 200 students from over 60 countries, on an integrated residential campus. It is located in the picturesque Sahyadhri Mountains of the Western Ghats. The concept of the campus plan evolved from that of a mandala. It centres the plan of this diverse, micro cosmos, around an academic quadrangle with passages radiating out from it, offering points of encounter along the way, as well as views towards the valleys in the distance. Using the auspicious North-South axis to intersect the sun\u2019s east-west movement in a plan centred on the academic quadrangle, a system of individual structures is laid out, each having their own character and identity, yet integrated via connecting walls and a strong architectural language of masonry and terracotta tile roofs. Set in the foreground of vast rugged, mountains, the building angles and geometry mimic the imagery of distant landscapes, and appear in the same scale due to the sizing impact of perspective; making the near large and the distant small; making the campus appear to be in the same scale as the vast landscape. These techniques of borrowing landscapes and of creating kinetic experiences through articulate choreography of movement are unique aspects of this campus in the mountains.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Nagaloka, Nagpur, Maharashtra''' }}\n\nThe [https://ccba.in/project/nagaloka/ Nagaloka institute] is located in the metropolis of Nagpur in central India. This institute is a centre for training in social work focused on the upliftment of disadvantaged communities.  The campus includes an entrance gate, public sanitary facilities, an administration building, the large [https://www.nagaloka.org/ Dhamma Hall] for discourses and lectures, a library, classrooms, a meditation pavilion or Vihara, a catering centre, guest houses, dormitories for men and women and dharmashalas accommodating visitors. The central focus is a statue of the Buddha aligned on a long promenade from the entry. A statue of Dr. Ambedkar commemorates his role in leading many followers to spiritual enlightenment and social upliftment. Situated in the outskirts of Nagpur, the campus configuration is influenced by the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarnath Deer Park at Sarnath], where the [[Buddha]] gave his Sermon of the Turning of the Wheel outlining the Fivefold Path. All of the structures are constructed of exposed brick, brick vaults, long span concrete shells and Kota stone flooring.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Kochi Refineries Limited, Kochi, Kerala''' }}\n\nThis corporate headquarters is located along the Kerala backwaters near Kochi, where a river turns sharply affording views up and down its edges, lined with coconut trees and thick forest cover. The design problem was to seek a holistic solution integrating the structural system, mechanical system and functional program into a system of \u201cfixed\u201d and \u201cflexible\u201d parts. Traditionally horizontal wood jaalis are employed to temper light and air, which is reflected in the employment of horizontal aluminium louvers in this work. It was essential that the headquarters of this energy enterprise be built around the concept of energy efficiency. The building is a glass cylinder, set inside a shading jaali tube, cutting down heat, while illuminating the interiors and saving energy. The strong building envelope allowed for space shaping within its geometric volume. The ground level structural glass walls are set back into the shade of the upper levels allowing the ground floor to act as one continuous open space flowing up through an atrium, while flowing out the ground level caf\u00e9 and entrance lobby into the horizontal natural vistas.\n\n==MAJOR PROJECTS (2000-2010)==\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies, Lonavala, Maharashtra''' }}\n\nThe Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies, a 55-acre green campus situated between Mumbai and Pune, is a green campus for pre-sea and post-sea maritime studies. The project was conceived by the owners of Executive Ship Management in Singapore to ensure the efficient, safe and environmentally sustainable management of their fleet of over sixty ships. The Architects were sent to sea for two weeks, as a pre-design sensitization exercise, and the conceptual designs were sketched at sea.\n\nLocated next to the Indrayani River, the campus consists of an administrative building, hostel accommodation for five hundred students with dining facilities, an auditorium and an amphitheatre. There is a large classroom building, a vast maritime workshop, a science building and extensive recreational facilities, including an Olympic-sized swimming pool.\n\nA \u201cShip on Campus\u201d is used to train young mariners. This is in fact a ship\u2019s eight storied, operational section that includes the engines, desalinization plant, sewerage treatment plant, generators, ventilating and air conditioning plants, tanker, fire fighting and other pumps, and navigation deck. \n\nMariners at sea live in miniature cities made of steel and glass and an attempt was made to replicate that environment in the campus. Taking inspiration from general ship accommodations, the student residences, in the centre of the campus, are in the form of a long, ship-like structure of five attached houses, each with their own entry stair, and commons areas and double seated rooms, each with an attached toilet.\n\nThis project was nearing completion just as the Suzlon One Earth project was initiated. Many green concepts that were explored at the Samudra Institute were built upon in the LEED-certified Suzlon campus. \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Suzlon One Earth Corporate Headquarters, Pune, Maharashtra''' }}\n\nSuzlon Energy Limited is a leading wind energy company based in Pune that aspired to create the most environmentally sensitive office campus in India. Covering about one hundred thousand square meters of built-up area on 10.4 acres of urban land, the project achieved international LEED Platinum and Indian TERI GRIHA top certifications. 8% of its annual energy is generated on-site through photovoltaic panels and windmills, at an incremental cost of 11%. At the time of completion there were no other campuses in India with this level of certification and cost efficiency. With an off-site wind energy farm supplying ninety-two percent of the potential four megawatt energy consumption, the campus is a net zero energy project. The design exclusively employs non-toxic and recycled materials. Water, energy, air, sewerage and trash are all sustainably managed on site.\n\nThe planning strategy derives its inspiration from historical campuses like Fatehpur Sikri and the Meenakshi Temple complex in Madurai. The design is created around a central gathering space, or Brahmasthan, with the sky as its ceiling, offering the entire campus visual access to extensive gardens. The anchoring visual element is a stone Deepstambh, a traditional Indian pillar of oil lamps, set in the centre of a Crescent-shaped Reflecting Pool. The central garden plaza, on a podium over parking and utilities, encourages interaction and discussion amongst the 2,300 colleagues, providing an iconic memory point for all who visit the campus.\n\nA series of served and server spaces were conceptualized, allowing adaptability to the transformational nature of evolving business patterns. The served spaces, where people work have flexible modular walls and furniture systems. These are served by more static cores housing wet areas, vertical utility ducts, fire stairs, elevators, entry and reception areas. \u201cModules\u201d were employed, like silo fire stairs; the benchmark glass cylinder ventilation chimneys, and the 8.4 by 8.4 meter structural modules. Aluminium louvers act as a protective skin allowing daylight and cross ventilation. A generic strategy was to provide seventy-five percent of the workstations with daylight and external views.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Supreme Court, Thimphu, Bhutan''' }}\n\nThe Supreme Court of Bhutan is one of the critical components of the Bhutan modernization project, the transformation of the monarchy into a constitutional democracy. The mandate was to create an iconic structure reflecting the importance of the Constitution and the culture from which the Constitution emerged.  The campus also spatially addresses the ancient Trashichhoe Dzong where the studio had completed an important extension, in the form of the National Ceremonial Plaza.\n\nThe limitation of building resources, craftsmen and technology, was a major design constraint. Prior to this design there had been several attempts by foreign architects, whose requirements of highly processed materials, technical construction equipment and construction management obviated implementation.\n\nThe completed campus consists of one full-bench Court and four single-bench Courts, supported by an Administrative Building, a Judicial Library, a Registrar\u2019s Building and Lawyers\u2019 Chambers. The design strategy addressed site, cultural, contextual, technological and functional factors. The use of Bhutanese local materials, craftspeople and building technologies was employed. The campus follows patterns of dimensions, iconography norms, colour and motif signifiers, and fabrication methods that are unique to the culture. There is a vast unwritten catalogue of details, motifs, joinery, column designs, etc. that the carpenters and masons know \u2018by heart,\u2019 and carry out by instinct, and not through \u2018measuring and building.\u2019\n\nThe urban design issues of the National Capital Precinct were also addressed through a site plan that centred the structures on a Judicial Plaza, aligning the full bench Supreme Court with the Trashichhoe Dzong, and specifically the ancient Utsi to the south. \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''IIM Calcutta, Kolkata, West Bengal''' }}\n\nThe Indian Institute of Management, Calcutta was the first in a series of business management institutions to be sponsored by the Government of India in the early 1960\u2019s to enhance the efficiency and transparency of commerce and industry. \n\nIn 2007 the Institute realized the need for a master plan and for increasing its student capacities. The proposed plan included hostels, executive training facilities, additional academic areas and major infrastructure additions. The residential complex would include a large dining and recreational facility on three levels. An executive hostel was also proposed with twenty-seven suites and one hundred and sixty-four single rooms apart from classrooms, syndicate rooms, lounges and dining facilities.\n\nThe construction language employs simple plastered facades and Kota stone flooring. Vertical silo staircase towers hold the four corners of the stepped hostels elevations.  Each of the hostel wings is composed of stepped sections, with private balconies stepping back up the exterior walls. Inside, open passages project into sky-lit atria, reaching out, one over the other, as they ascend. The residential nneighbourhoodopens up through landscaped terraces and gardens onto placid lotus ponds in a verdant landscape. The residential neighborhood is connected to the academic quadrangle by an iconic tubular steel pedestrian bridge, crossing a forty-three meters wide water pond. In the academic quadrangle, a dilapidated school was demolished and moved, making way for a larger open space. \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Kirloskar Institute of Advanced Management Studies, Pune, Maharashtra''' }}\n\nThe Kirloskar Institute of Advanced Management Studies was conceptualised by the Kirloskar Group of Industries, one of the oldest family owned industrial establishments in Western India, to create a a generation of management professionals suited to the modern business environment. \n\nLocated on the periphery of Pune on the Sahyadhri mountain range, the site slopes down from an arterial road. From the entrance, a series of courtyards step down onto subsequent lower terraces, and each terrace is devoted to a core function focused around a courtyard. The entry and the administration were kept at the top; mid-career executive training on the next lower terrace courtyard; masters in business administration, first and second years, on the next two lower level terraces, and the library at the lowest terrace. In each of these courtyards, one side is devoted to faculty offices and the others to classrooms. \n\nOn the other side of the site the residential area begins with an residential entry for executive management candidates on the higher terrace, and subsequent dropping terraces dedicated to accommodate postgraduate student hostels and common areas. The recreational area on the lowermost terrace has a swimming pool and multi-purpose halls for yoga and a gym. There are tennis courts and other sports areas at the lower end of the site where a water collection pond and cisterns store rainwater.\n\nExposed concrete with white rough plaster on brick infill walls, natural Kota Stone floors and sloped copper aluminium roofs, mirroring the mountainous terrain, have been used in the project. \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Lodha Belmondo, Pune, Maharashtra''' }}\n\nNestled between the Expressway and the Pavana River, this 100-acre township boasts of picturesque views of the Western Ghats and the adjoining river while maintaining easy access to the employment hubs and emerging residential areas of Pune. \n\nDevelopment Control regulations required wide setbacks from the expressway and the adjoining river. These setbacks, along with a large swathe of land unfit for construction through the centre, limited development to small pockets along the periphery of the site. To make the project financially viable for the developers, the Architect proposed a high-rise construction to utilize maximum FSI. This approach also freed up more than 70% of the site\u2019s groundcover to develop amenities including an 18-hole golf course and a world-class club house.\n\nThe housing scheme takes cues from the global trend of \u201cplus one\u201d that focuses not only on the private living spaces but also on the common and public spaces, amenities, and the surrounding environment as significant value-adding enhancements. The state-of-the-art livings spaces are a mix of flats and villas. These varying typologies have been seamlessly assembled, both functionally and aesthetically.\n\nThe large facades of these imposing vertical towers have been broken down into horizontal elements. The composition of the aluminum louvers, the cantilevered balconies and recessed windows, appropriately complements this considerable upright mass.  The terracotta-faced staircase and elevator cores rise up to resemble ancient temples of the medieval period. The complete fa\u00e7ade is bound together by a projecting frame of masonry along its edge. \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''COEP Girls\u2019 Hostel, Pune''' }}\n\nInitiated in 1854, the College of Engineering at Pune (COEP) is one of the oldest engineering colleges in Asia. Over decades the 36-acre campus has been encroached upon for expanding highways, railway lines, arterial roads, and recently flyovers, resulting in five fragmented land parcels, one of which is covered by low income squatters. A new management in 2006 formulated a vision to double its student intake, enhance its facilities and to increase its residential hostels, especially for women.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''Women\u2019s\u2019 Residence''' }}\n\nThe women\u2019s residence was the first initiative in this campus development program. This hostel is envisioned to anchor a pedestrian stem of four, twelve-storied structures, positioning common spaces on the ground level and locating residential rooms above. The strategy for the residences is to situate two bedrooms on either side of a wet core accessed through a dry balcony, lent privacy by concrete jaalis that filter views. With the ground floor dedicated to common facilities, and the roof garden level devoted to a gym, clinic, laundry and apartments for mentors, the remaining ten floors, of twenty rooms each, accommodate six hundred women within the college campus.\n\nThe ground floor level of this structure hosts a cutout-porch, through which the planned stem, or campus street, will later pass. To one side of this porch lies a coffee shop, and on the other side is the hostel entrance lobby, with elevators and vertical stair. There is also an entry into the large dining room, with cooking facilities behind it. This structure is wedged into a corner site of the residential campus with one side opening onto a narrow garden promenade, shared with a hundred year old, ground and two floors, boys\u2019 hostel that has been renovated into a postgraduate women\u2019s residence. \n\n== MAJOR PROJECTS (2010-2020) ==\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''FORBES MARSHALL GREEN FIELD INDUSTRIAL PARK, PUNE, MAHARASHTRA''' }}\n\nThe [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forbes_Marshall Forbes family] had been working out of antiquated, inefficient and chaotic structures, that grew according to need in an ad hoc manner over decades. Sensing the need for change the clients and the architects conceptualized the idea of factories turning into creative work-studios of highly qualified thinker-doers, using high-tech manufacturing.\n\nThe concept of pollution free, efficient work pavilions, set in a green garden ambiance, was jointly conceived by the architect and the clients. It was also envisioned as a testament to a social commitment to safety, hygiene and sustainability.\n\nSpread over fifty acres, the [https://ccba.in/project/forbes-marshall-greenfield-field-industrial-campus/ industrial campus] focuses on a central green spine of gardens, water bodies and breakout areas. The first phase of the campus is composed of two large manufacturing pavilions supported by utility structures and linking roads. \n\nThe architect\u2019s ambition was for the most unskilled worker and the most senior manager to feel a sense of pride in their place of work. \n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''BAJAJ INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY, WARDHA, MAHARASHTRA''' }}\n\nBajaj Institute of Technology is a college which would impart quality Engineering education in the [[Wardha]] district of Maharashtra. Set up under the [http://bit.shikshamandal.org/ ShikshaMandal] (a 100-year old educational trust set up and managed by the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahul_Bajaj Bajaj family]) this college campus is designed as a temple for learning.\n\nEncompassing the core disciplines of engineering, the campus is designed to set the standards not only for the quality of education, but also, for Architectural aesthetics and ambience. The campus of [http://ccba.in/project/bajaj-institute-of-management/ Bajaj Institute of Technology], is designed on the principles of sustainability and the same is echoed in the facets of design from the planning through to construction.\n\nThe campus is designed as a great place to live and learn; the environs of the campus makes people feel close to nature; it will feel like a community and function like a university; it will have gardens, courtyards and promenades where people meet and interact. It will engender intellectual friendship and encourage the search for truth.\n\nA lake is contemplated at the lower end of the site which will store rainwater. It balances the temperature of the campus by evaporation. Courtyards, Central library, Deep stambh, Water body and Triangular voids are the major landscape and building elements which ties the campus as nodes of an organic structure.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''AZIM PREMJI UNIVERSITY, BENGALURU, KARNATAKA''' }}\n\nThe [https://azimpremjiuniversity.edu.in/SitePages/school-of-education-programmes-ma-education.aspx?gclid=Cj0KCQiAovfvBRCRARIsADEmbRJZM3ooRP9usZo45cRintMMhGB5TRLVkW4UU0gGWGtDAxZm1Q8fvf0aAmJpEALw_wcB Azim Premji University] is being built on a 36 hectares site in the periphery of the Bengaluru metropolitan region. The university is an integral component of a national strategy by the [https://azimpremjifoundation.org/associates?gclid=Cj0KCQiAovfvBRCRARIsADEmbRKab2dzYxOUndITAZMQ5GmcA47-aQoPTjbWauyUQBZTQRrdm95KGlIaAhdKEALw_wcB Azim Premji Foundation], a philanthropic organization, to improve primary education in India.\n\nThe academic area at the entrance to the campus includes the library, auditorium, classrooms, faculty study rooms, laboratories and lecture halls. These activities are linked with each other through a system of covered arcades and courtyards, around and within which various functions are located due their mutual synergies and complementarities.\n\nA hierarchy of social spaces facilitates various kinds of idea exchanges, from one-on-one discussions, to group discussions, debates, lectures and dramas. An individual can find their own place to contemplate, or discover a corner to question a friend. They can sit in a breakout space freely exchanging opinions, criticisms and new ideas. Thus, it is the informal learning spaces that compliment and amplify the formal places.\n\n{{ font color | #2445AD| '''IIT HYDERABAD, HYDERABAD, TELANGANA''' }}\n\nThe [https://www.iith.ac.in/ Indian Institute of Technology at Hyderabad] is a 272 hectares campus, located on the Hyderabad -Mumbai Highway, at a peripheral site of the metropolitan area.\n\nThe [https://ccba.in/project/indian-institute-of-technology/ Lecture Hall Complex] is composed of fifteen auditoria accommodating seventy-five to eight hundred students each, holding over three thousand, two hundred students when fully occupied. The Lecture Hall Complex sits at the junction of the two primary pedestrian movement paths in the campus. \n\nThe sites for the [https://ccba.in/project/housing-at-india-institute-of-technology/ Faculty and Staff Housing] are located in a residential neighbourhood of the Master Plan. The Faculty Housing site employs a garden podium that links four, eighteen storied apartment towers, and provides covered parking for two hundred and fifty vehicles.\n\nOther designs include the Student Commons, covered by a large tensile structure, sheltering a subterranean complex of activity spaces stepping down into a sequence of activities, leading to a large, central functional space for dances, dramas and performances. The concept was drawn from India\u2019s step well traditions, leading one down into shaded cool spaces, away from the intruding summer sun\u2019s rays.\n\n== Career ==\nBenninger studied under [[Josep Lluis Sert]] and worked in his studio. He was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of the noted economist [[Barbara Ward]] and a member of the [[Delos Symposium]] group, contributing articles to the journal ''[[Ekistics]]''. He was influenced by the group's founder, [[Constantinos Doxiadis]] who led the Ekistics movement. This brought him into association with [[Buckminster Fuller]], [[Arnold Toynbee]], [[Margaret Mead]] and Jaquline Tyrwhitt.\n\nOn the invitation of [[B. V. Doshi]], in 1971 he resigned from his tenured post at Harvard and shifted to [[Ahmedabad]], India as a [[Ford Foundation]] Advisor to  the Ahmedabad Educational Society, where he founded the School of Planning.<ref>Lang, Jon T., A concise history of modern architecture in India, 2002, Page 45</ref>  In 1976 he shifted to [[Pune]], India, where he founded the [[Center for Development Studies and Activities]].<ref>[http://www.archpresspk.com/m10_interview.htm Archpresspk.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707160139/http://www.archpresspk.com/m10_interview.htm |date=2011-07-07 }}</ref>  In 1983 Benninger wrote the Theme Paper for the United Nations Commission on Human Settlements 1984.  In 1986 he was engaged by the [[Asian Development Bank]] to author their position paper on [[Urban Development]], arguing successfully the case for extending financial assistance to the urban development sector.  Benninger is on the Board of Editors of ''CITIES'' journal (UK),<ref>[http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaleditorialboard.cws_home/30396/editorialboard Elsevier.com]</ref> and on the Board of the United States Educational Foundation ([[Fulbright Foundation]]) in India.  He is a Distinguished Professor at the [[Centre for Environmental and Planning Technology University]], Ahmedabad,<ref>[http://www.spcept.ac.in/faculty_profile.aspx?pg=fac&sub=fac Spcept.ac.in] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523052840/http://www.spcept.ac.in/faculty_profile.aspx?pg=fac&sub=fac |date=2010-05-23 }}</ref> and on the Board of Governors of the [[School of Planning and Architecture]], New Delhi.\n\nWhile in Ahmedabad he innovated the concept of [[Site and Services]], an approach to housing providing access to shelter via developed small plots, allowing poor families to construct their own homes, according to their means.  For  the [[World Bank]] and the Madras Urban Development Authority 1973 he designed over 20,000 such units in four locations, the largest being at Arambakum in [[Chennai]].  With the advent of institutional housing finance in India 1972 he created a unique neighborhood of small ground level houses for about five hundred households in [[Jamnagar]], [[Gujarat]].  This was the first shelter program funded by the [[Government of India]] for the economically weaker section of society.  In 1976\u201379, using funding from the [[Housing and Urban Development Corporation]] (HUDCO), he built a township for low income households at Yusafguda, in [[Hyderabad, Andhra Pradesh|Hyderabad]] with over two thousand houses, public amenities and shopping centres.  This was the first project of the [[Hyderabad Urban Development Authority]] and provided owners with road access, street lights, storm drains, electricity and sanitary cores. Around these core facilities low income families could construct their own houses.  For the [[World Bank]] and the Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authority, Benninger was part of a team that devised the (slum) Busti Improvement Program. This approach  brought sanitation, potable water, electricity, storm drains, paved lanes with  street lighting and community services to millions of  low income citizens of [[Kolkata]].\n\nArchitectural Work=\nBenninger's best known architectural works are a cluster of academic and educational campuses in the mountainous region between [[Mumbai]] and [[Pune]] in India. These include the [[Center for Development Studies and Activities]], the [[Mahindra United World College of India]], the [[Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies]], the [[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]], the Kirloskar Institute of Advanced Management Studies and the [[International School Aamby]]. The Centre for Life Sciences Health and Medicine in Pune is a radical departure from his earlier work.<ref>[http://www.g-therapy.org/index.php/center-campus.html G-therapy.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100512195745/http://www.g-therapy.org/index.php/center-campus.html |date=2010-05-12 }}</ref> Other important works are the [[Kochi Refineries]] Corporate Headquarters in Kerala, the [[Alliance Francaise]] in Ahmedabad and [[SOS Children's Villages]] in [[Kolkata]] and Bawana outside of [[Delhi]]. The new campuses for the [[Indian Institute of Management Calcutta]] and the [[College of Engineering, Pune]] are nearing completion. Benninger was recently awarded the [[Azim Premji University]] in Bangalore and the [[Bajaj Group|Bajaj]] Institute of Technology in [[Wardha]] where he has built the Bajaj Science Centre.\n\nThe [[Mahindra United World College of India]] won international recognition as the recipient of  the ''[[Business Week]]''/[[Architectural Record]] Award for Excellence in the year 2000. This Award was sponsored jointly with the [[American Institute of Architects]]. ''Business Week'' called the [[Mahindra United World College of India]] one of the ten super structures of the world in the year 2000.<ref>[http://www.businessweek.com/2000/00_45/c3706129.htm Businessweek.com]</ref> The project also won the Designer of the Year Award <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archlib.njit.edu/aboutus/benningerlecture.php |title=Archlib.njit.edu |access-date=2010-06-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805200851/http://archlib.njit.edu/aboutus/benningerlecture.php |archive-date=2010-08-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in 1999. The [[Kochi Refineries]] Headquarters Building won the award as one of India's two best office buildings in 2005, sponsored by the [[Indian Architect and Builder]] \"awards for working spaces\".\n[[File:Ymcalakecampsitenilshi.jpg|thumb|Camp Managers Bungalow at [[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]]]]\n[[Image:Indiahouse.jpg|thumb|India House, studio and residence of Prof.Benninger, in [[Pune]], [[Maharashtra]].]]\n[[Image:Tshechuground.jpg|thumb|Tshechu Ground or the National Ceremonial Plaza in [[Thimphu]], [[Bhutan]].]] \n[[File:Hyderabadiit-2.jpg|thumb|[[Indian Institute of Technology Hyderabad|IIT Hyderabad]], Telangana, India]]\nThe [[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]] won the Archies Award for the best Institutional Building 2006 and the [[Indian Institute of Architects]] Award for the Best Public Building 2006. The British Society for Design and the Architecture Plus Design journal awarded Benninger the [[Recognition in Design]] (RED) Award as the Best Architect in  India in November 2006. This was the first RED award given in India. His building [[Samundra Institute of Maritime]] Studies was selected for the Indian Institute of Archietcs as the Best Public Building for the year 2008 and by the J. K. Cement Awards as the best Institution in the year 2009. It won the Institute of Structural Steel Design and Growth Award 2009 as one of the two best steel structures in India.\n\nBenninger's planning work includes development plans for six regional capitals in [[Sri Lanka]], three new towns in [[Bhutan]], the Development Plans of [[Kalyan, India|Kalyan]] and [[Thane]] in the [[Mumbai Metropolitan Region]], the plans for twenty-eight urban centres in [[Madhya Pradesh]] and the Capital City of [[Bhutan]], [[Thimphu]]. For Nepal he designed their decentralized planning methodology 1989 and for [[Indonesia]] their Shelter Sector for the Indonesian National Rural Development Program 1979-81. Benninger guided the planners of the Katenga Regional Development Authority in their design of the new economic region in Terengganu, an emerging region in the North-eastern region of [[Malaysia]]. Benninger's work in urban design, city management and town planning resulted in his [[Principles of Intelligent Urbanism]], which guided his planning of the new capital of Bhutan.<ref>[http://www.dudh.gov.bt/Thimphustructural/Index.html Dudh.gov.bt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100623013525/http://www.dudh.gov.bt/Thimphustructural/Index.html |date=2010-06-23 }}</ref>\n\nArchitectural works in progress include the new campus for the [[Indian Institute of Management Calcutta]]; the Indoor Air Conditioned Stadium at Ahmedabad; The Governance Center at Hyderabad and second campus of KIAMS at Pune.[[Suzlon One Earth]], of the [[Suzlon]] Wind Energy Company, India House, new studios for Christopber Charles Benninger Architects were completed recently.\n\nThe studio in [[Bhutan]] has completed [[Tshechu]] Ground, a major ceremonial plaza and pavilion for the annual National Buddhist festival and the coronation site for the Fifth King;and the Supreme Court of Bhutan; and the first four of the ten Secretariat Ministries that will form the National Secretariat Complex are under construction. The Bhutan Studio is also designing the new UN HOUSE in Bhutan.\n\n===List of Projects (Chronology)===\n\n* '''1972 - 1973'''\tThe Bhanuben Parekh Villa, Bhavnagar, Gujarat \n* '''1972'''\t        The Low-income Housing Township, 500 houses, Jamnagar, Gujarat \n* '''1973 - 1975'''     The Site and Services Shelter Programme, 20000 houses, Chennai, Tamil Nadu\n* '''1973 - 1976''' \tThe Theological (Alliance Francaise) Library, Ahmedabad, Gujarat \n* '''1973 - 1975'''   \tSOS Children Village, Bawana, New Delhi \n* '''1975 - 1978'''   \tSOS Children Village, Kolkata, West Bengal\n* '''1975 - 1978'''   \tYusafguda low-income township, Hyderabad, Telangana \n* '''1980 - 1982'''    \tDevelopment Plan for the city and region of Jaffna, Sri Lanka\n* '''1980 - 1990'''   \tThane Development Management System Report, Maharashtra \n* '''1980 - 1990'''  \tKalyan Development Management System Report, Maharashtra \n* '''1980 - 1990''' \t28 Urban Centers, Madhya Pradesh\n* '''1983 - 1992'''   \tGalle Town structure plan, Sri Lanka\n* '''1986 - 1989'''\tCenter for Development Studies and Activities, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''1988 - 1989'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Hostel, Lohegaon, Pune\n* '''1989 - 1990'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Center, Dapodi, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''1989 - 1990'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Girls' Hostel, Vishrantwadi, Pune\n* '''1990 - 1991'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Boys' Hostel, Wardha, Maharashtra\n* '''1990 - 1991'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Boys' Hostel, Aurangabad, MH\n* '''1994 - 1996'''\tKrushi Vigyan Kendra, Jalna, Maharashtra\n* '''1996''' - \t        Nagarjuna Vihara and Institute(Nagloka), Nagpur, Maharashtra \n* '''1996 - 1998'''\tLibrary Extension, Gokhale Institute of Political Sciences, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''1996 - 1998'''\tInstitute of Social Science, New Delhi \n* '''1996 - 1998'''\tThe Mahindra United World College of India, Mulshi, Maharashtra \n* '''1997 - 2002'''\tCorporate Headquarters, Kochi Refineries Limited, Kochi, Kerala \n* '''1998 - 2002'''\tYMCA International Campsite, Nilshi, Maharashtra \n* '''1998 - 1999'''\tQuest International School, Alibaug, Maharashtra\n* '''1998 - 2000'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Girls' Hostel, Nagpur, Maharashtra\n* '''1999 - 2000'''\tStudent Village, Center for Development Studies and Activities, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''1999''' - \t        The Directorate of Town and Country Planning, Hyderabad, Telangana, (Competition Winner, Under Construction) \n* '''2001 - 2003'''\tBasant Bahar Housing, Ahmedabad, Gujarat\n* '''2001 - 2003'''\tCenturion hotel, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2001 - 2004'''\tCenter for Life Sciences Health and Medicine(previously CNDCM), Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2001 - 2002'''\tThimpu Structure Plan, Bhutan \n* '''2001 - 2004'''\tTAIN Square, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2003'''\t        Structure Plan for Gelephug, Damphu and Samtshi, Bhutan\n* '''2003'''\t        Urban design of the Dzong Precinct, Thimpu, Bhutan \n* '''2004 - 2007'''\tSamundra Institute of Maritime Studies, Lonavala, Maharashtra \n* '''2004 - 2005'''\tAshoka Primary School, Nasik, Maharashtra\n* '''2005 - 2009'''\tSuzlon One Earth Global Headquarters, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2005 - 2013'''\tRoyal Supreme Courts Complex, Thimphu, Bhutan\n* '''2005 - 2008'''\tNational Ceremonial Plaza, Thimphu, Bhutan\n* '''2006 - 2010'''\tBajaj IT Tower, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2006 - 2011'''\tIndian Institute of Management, Calcutta, West Bengal (Phase 1) \n* '''2006 - 2008'''\tAamby Valley International School, Lonavala, Maharashtra (Phase 1) \n* '''2006 - 2008'''\tIndia House, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2007 - 2009'''\tMirchandani Office Building, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2007 - 2013'''\tUN House, Thimphu, Bhutan\n* '''2007 - 2009'''\tSandhya Vakil House, Panvel\n* '''2007'''           \tCollege of Engineering Pune - Master Plan\n* '''2008 - 2010'''\tBajaj Science Educational Centre, Wardha, Maharashtra\n* '''2008 - 2013'''\tKirloskar Institute of Advanced Management Studies, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2008 -''' \t        Life Care Hospital and Research Centre, Udgir, Maharashtra\n* '''2009 -''' \t        Lodha Belmondo, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2009 - 2010'''\tStructure Plan for Denchi, Bhutan\n* '''2009 - 2012'''\tAcademic Building, College of Engineering, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2009 - 2012'''\tGirls' Hostel, College of Engineering, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2009''' - \t        Bajaj Institute of Technology, Wardha, Maharashtra\n* '''2010''' -           \tBajaj Management College, Nagpur, Maharashtra\n* '''2010''' -           \tAzim Premji University, Bengaluru, Karnataka\n* '''2011''' -      \tNew Era High School, Panchgani, Maharashtra \n* '''2011''' -      \t[[Indian Institute of Technology Hyderabad]], Telangana (Phase 1A)\n* '''2011 - 2013'''\tForbes Marshall Industrial Campus, Chakan, Pune (Phase 1)\n* '''2011'''-       \tIndian Institute of Management, Calcutta, West Bengal (Phase 2) \n* '''2013''' -      \t Indian Institute of Technology, Hyderabad, Telangana (Phase 1B)\n* '''2013''' -      \tNTTF, Katpadi, Tamil Nadu\n* '''2013''' -       \tEnvironmental Centre at Empress Garden, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2013''' -      \tKrohne Marshall Industrial Expansion, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2013''' -      \tKEM Hospital redevelopment, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2013''' -       \tBoys' Hostel, College of Engineering, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2014''' -      \tRedevelopment of Indrayani B, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2014''' -      \tForbes Marshall Industrial Campus, Chakan, Pune (Phase 2)\n\n==Awards and Recognition==\nIn April 2010 Professor Benninger was awarded the Architect for the Decade Award his contribution to the profession of architecture over that period. Over the past four years, on three occasions, the Indian Institute of Architects has honored him with the award of Best Public Building of the Year for his designs of the [[Centre for Life Sciences, Health and Medicine]], the [[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]] and for the [[Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies]].  The design for [[Suzlon One Earth]] has been honored by the Architects, Engineers, Surveyors Association of Pune as the Best Architectural Work in the City in 2009 and it was recently named the Most Sustainable Building in India, in a national competition. It is a [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum and Five Star [[Teri Griha]] building. Christopher Benninger is currently the sixth winner in India of the Golden Architect Award for Lifetime Achievement (2006) that was conferred in May 2007 by the A+D and Spectrum Foundation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://mobilepaper.timesofindia.com/mobile.aspx?article=yes&pageid=7&sectid=edid=&edlabel=PMIR&mydateHid=24-02-2010&pubname=Mirror+-+Pune&edname=&articleid=Ar00700&publabel=MM | title=AESA HONOUR FOR BENNINGER | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> Over the past seventeen years, six Indian architects have been honored with the Great Master's Award,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Master-of-concrete-dreams/258139/ |title=Expressindia.com |access-date=2010-06-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005150938/http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Master-of-concrete-dreams/258139/ |archive-date=2012-10-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and in 2007 Professor Benninger became the seventh awardee. Over several years he was recognised as one of the top ten architects in India by ''Construction World'' Magazine.<ref>[http://www.constructionupdate.com/asapp/events/CWABawards/archives_cw_2007.html Constructionupdate.com] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120722153643/http://www.constructionupdate.com/asapp/events/CWABawards/archives_cw_2007.html |date=2012-07-22 }}</ref>\nHis firm, Christopher Charles Benninger Architects, has a team of thirty-five professionals with studio in [[Pune]]. He has associated a group of technical consultants in New Delhi, Mumbai, Bangalore and Pune in the areas of structural services, landscape and interior design. CCBA offers comprehensive architectural services from design through supervision.  In recognition of his contributions to the architectural and planning professions in India, Christopher Charles Benninger has been honoured as the first recipient of the (RED) Recognition of Excellence in Design Award (2006). This was conferred by the [[Royal Society of Designers]] and\nArchitecture Plus Design journal in India on an Industrial Designer, on an Interior Designer and on an architect.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ekistics]]\n*[[Mahindra United World College of India]]\n*[[Principles of Intelligent Urbanism]]\n*[[Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies]]\n*[[Suzlon One Earth]]\n*[[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.ccba.in}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benninger, Christopher Charles}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American urban planners]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Design faculty]]\n[[Category:Architects from Ohio]]\n[[Category:American male artists of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American male artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American architects]]\n[[Category:People from Gainesville, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=Repeat and unorganized info|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name = Christopher Charles Benninger\n| image = Christopher Charles Benninger.JPG\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1942|11|23}}\n| birth_place = Hamilton, Ohio, USA\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = American-Indian\n| alma_mater  = [[Harvard Graduate School of Design|Harvard GSD]]<br />[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]\n| awards = Great Master Architect of India\n| practice = CCBA Designs\n| significant_buildings = Mahindra United World College, Suzlon One Earth, India House\n| significant_projects = [[Royal Supreme Court, Bhutan]]; College of Engineering Pune, Indian Institute of Technology, Hyderabad\n}}\n[[Image:Suzlon One Earth Headquarters, Pune, India. Photo A. Ramprasad (10).jpg|thumb|[[Suzlon One Earth]], designed by Christopher Benninger, in [[Pune]], [[Maharashtra]].]]\n\n'''Christopher Charles Benninger''' is an American-Indian architect and planner..\n\n== Career ==\nBenninger studied under [[Josep Lluis Sert]] and worked in his studio. He was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of the noted economist [[Barbara Ward]] and a member of the [[Delos Symposium]] group, contributing articles to the journal ''[[Ekistics]]''. He was influenced by the group's founder, [[Constantinos Doxiadis]] who led the Ekistics movement. This brought him into association with [[Buckminster Fuller]], [[Arnold Toynbee]], [[Margaret Mead]] and Jaquline Tyrwhitt.\n\nOn the invitation of [[B. V. Doshi]], in 1971 he resigned from his tenured post at Harvard and shifted to [[Ahmedabad]], India as a [[Ford Foundation]] Advisor to  the Ahmedabad Educational Society, where he founded the School of Planning.<ref>Lang, Jon T., A concise history of modern architecture in India, 2002, Page 45</ref>  In 1976 he shifted to [[Pune]], India, where he founded the [[Center for Development Studies and Activities]].<ref>[http://www.archpresspk.com/m10_interview.htm Archpresspk.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707160139/http://www.archpresspk.com/m10_interview.htm |date=2011-07-07 }}</ref>  In 1983 Benninger wrote the Theme Paper for the United Nations Commission on Human Settlements 1984.  In 1986 he was engaged by the [[Asian Development Bank]] to author their position paper on [[Urban Development]], arguing successfully the case for extending financial assistance to the urban development sector.  Benninger is on the Board of Editors of ''CITIES'' journal (UK),<ref>[http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaleditorialboard.cws_home/30396/editorialboard Elsevier.com]</ref> and on the Board of the United States Educational Foundation ([[Fulbright Foundation]]) in India.  He is a Distinguished Professor at the [[Centre for Environmental and Planning Technology University]], Ahmedabad,<ref>[http://www.spcept.ac.in/faculty_profile.aspx?pg=fac&sub=fac Spcept.ac.in] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523052840/http://www.spcept.ac.in/faculty_profile.aspx?pg=fac&sub=fac |date=2010-05-23 }}</ref> and on the Board of Governors of the [[School of Planning and Architecture]], New Delhi.\n\nWhile in Ahmedabad he innovated the concept of [[Site and Services]], an approach to housing providing access to shelter via developed small plots, allowing poor families to construct their own homes, according to their means.  For  the [[World Bank]] and the Madras Urban Development Authority 1973 he designed over 20,000 such units in four locations, the largest being at Arambakum in [[Chennai]].  With the advent of institutional housing finance in India 1972 he created a unique neighborhood of small ground level houses for about five hundred households in [[Jamnagar]], [[Gujarat]].  This was the first shelter program funded by the [[Government of India]] for the economically weaker section of society.  In 1976\u201379, using funding from the [[Housing and Urban Development Corporation]] (HUDCO), he built a township for low income households at Yusafguda, in [[Hyderabad, Andhra Pradesh|Hyderabad]] with over two thousand houses, public amenities and shopping centres.  This was the first project of the [[Hyderabad Urban Development Authority]] and provided owners with road access, street lights, storm drains, electricity and sanitary cores. Around these core facilities low income families could construct their own houses.  For the [[World Bank]] and the Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authority, Benninger was part of a team that devised the (slum) Busti Improvement Program. This approach  brought sanitation, potable water, electricity, storm drains, paved lanes with  street lighting and community services to millions of  low income citizens of [[Kolkata]].\n\nArchitectural Work=\nBenninger's best known architectural works are a cluster of academic and educational campuses in the mountainous region between [[Mumbai]] and [[Pune]] in India. These include the [[Center for Development Studies and Activities]], the [[Mahindra United World College of India]], the [[Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies]], the [[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]], the Kirloskar Institute of Advanced Management Studies and the [[International School Aamby]]. The Centre for Life Sciences Health and Medicine in Pune is a radical departure from his earlier work.<ref>[http://www.g-therapy.org/index.php/center-campus.html G-therapy.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100512195745/http://www.g-therapy.org/index.php/center-campus.html |date=2010-05-12 }}</ref> Other important works are the [[Kochi Refineries]] Corporate Headquarters in Kerala, the [[Alliance Francaise]] in Ahmedabad and [[SOS Children's Villages]] in [[Kolkata]] and Bawana outside of [[Delhi]]. The new campuses for the [[Indian Institute of Management Calcutta]] and the [[College of Engineering, Pune]] are nearing completion. Benninger was recently awarded the [[Azim Premji University]] in Bangalore and the [[Bajaj Group|Bajaj]] Institute of Technology in [[Wardha]] where he has built the Bajaj Science Centre.\n\nThe [[Mahindra United World College of India]] won international recognition as the recipient of  the ''[[Business Week]]''/[[Architectural Record]] Award for Excellence in the year 2000. This Award was sponsored jointly with the [[American Institute of Architects]]. ''Business Week'' called the [[Mahindra United World College of India]] one of the ten super structures of the world in the year 2000.<ref>[http://www.businessweek.com/2000/00_45/c3706129.htm Businessweek.com]</ref> The project also won the Designer of the Year Award <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archlib.njit.edu/aboutus/benningerlecture.php |title=Archlib.njit.edu |access-date=2010-06-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805200851/http://archlib.njit.edu/aboutus/benningerlecture.php |archive-date=2010-08-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in 1999. The [[Kochi Refineries]] Headquarters Building won the award as one of India's two best office buildings in 2005, sponsored by the [[Indian Architect and Builder]] \"awards for working spaces\".\n[[File:Ymcalakecampsitenilshi.jpg|thumb|Camp Managers Bungalow at [[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]]]]\n[[Image:Indiahouse.jpg|thumb|India House, studio and residence of Prof.Benninger, in [[Pune]], [[Maharashtra]].]]\n[[Image:Tshechuground.jpg|thumb|Tshechu Ground or the National Ceremonial Plaza in [[Thimphu]], [[Bhutan]].]] \n[[File:Hyderabadiit-2.jpg|thumb|[[Indian Institute of Technology Hyderabad|IIT Hyderabad]], Telangana, India]]\nThe [[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]] won the Archies Award for the best Institutional Building 2006 and the [[Indian Institute of Architects]] Award for the Best Public Building 2006. The British Society for Design and the Architecture Plus Design journal awarded Benninger the [[Recognition in Design]] (RED) Award as the Best Architect in  India in November 2006. This was the first RED award given in India. His building [[Samundra Institute of Maritime]] Studies was selected for the Indian Institute of Archietcs as the Best Public Building for the year 2008 and by the J. K. Cement Awards as the best Institution in the year 2009. It won the Institute of Structural Steel Design and Growth Award 2009 as one of the two best steel structures in India.\n\nBenninger's planning work includes development plans for six regional capitals in [[Sri Lanka]], three new towns in [[Bhutan]], the Development Plans of [[Kalyan, India|Kalyan]] and [[Thane]] in the [[Mumbai Metropolitan Region]], the plans for twenty-eight urban centres in [[Madhya Pradesh]] and the Capital City of [[Bhutan]], [[Thimphu]]. For Nepal he designed their decentralized planning methodology 1989 and for [[Indonesia]] their Shelter Sector for the Indonesian National Rural Development Program 1979-81. Benninger guided the planners of the Katenga Regional Development Authority in their design of the new economic region in Terengganu, an emerging region in the North-eastern region of [[Malaysia]]. Benninger's work in urban design, city management and town planning resulted in his [[Principles of Intelligent Urbanism]], which guided his planning of the new capital of Bhutan.<ref>[http://www.dudh.gov.bt/Thimphustructural/Index.html Dudh.gov.bt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100623013525/http://www.dudh.gov.bt/Thimphustructural/Index.html |date=2010-06-23 }}</ref>\n\nArchitectural works in progress include the new campus for the [[Indian Institute of Management Calcutta]]; the Indoor Air Conditioned Stadium at Ahmedabad; The Governance Center at Hyderabad and second campus of KIAMS at Pune.[[Suzlon One Earth]], of the [[Suzlon]] Wind Energy Company, India House, new studios for Christopber Charles Benninger Architects were completed recently.\n\nThe studio in [[Bhutan]] has completed [[Tshechu]] Ground, a major ceremonial plaza and pavilion for the annual National Buddhist festival and the coronation site for the Fifth King;and the Supreme Court of Bhutan; and the first four of the ten Secretariat Ministries that will form the National Secretariat Complex are under construction. The Bhutan Studio is also designing the new UN HOUSE in Bhutan.\n\n===List of Projects (Chronology)===\n\n* '''1972 - 1973'''\tThe Bhanuben Parekh Villa, Bhavnagar, Gujarat \n* '''1972'''\t        The Low-income Housing Township, 500 houses, Jamnagar, Gujarat \n* '''1973 - 1975'''     The Site and Services Shelter Programme, 20000 houses, Chennai, Tamil Nadu\n* '''1973 - 1976''' \tThe Theological (Alliance Francaise) Library, Ahmedabad, Gujarat \n* '''1973 - 1975'''   \tSOS Children Village, Bawana, New Delhi \n* '''1975 - 1978'''   \tSOS Children Village, Kolkata, West Bengal\n* '''1975 - 1978'''   \tYusafguda low-income township, Hyderabad, Telangana \n* '''1980 - 1982'''    \tDevelopment Plan for the city and region of Jaffna, Sri Lanka\n* '''1980 - 1990'''   \tThane Development Management System Report, Maharashtra \n* '''1980 - 1990'''  \tKalyan Development Management System Report, Maharashtra \n* '''1980 - 1990''' \t28 Urban Centers, Madhya Pradesh\n* '''1983 - 1992'''   \tGalle Town structure plan, Sri Lanka\n* '''1986 - 1989'''\tCenter for Development Studies and Activities, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''1988 - 1989'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Hostel, Lohegaon, Pune\n* '''1989 - 1990'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Center, Dapodi, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''1989 - 1990'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Girls' Hostel, Vishrantwadi, Pune\n* '''1990 - 1991'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Boys' Hostel, Wardha, Maharashtra\n* '''1990 - 1991'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Boys' Hostel, Aurangabad, MH\n* '''1994 - 1996'''\tKrushi Vigyan Kendra, Jalna, Maharashtra\n* '''1996''' - \t        Nagarjuna Vihara and Institute(Nagloka), Nagpur, Maharashtra \n* '''1996 - 1998'''\tLibrary Extension, Gokhale Institute of Political Sciences, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''1996 - 1998'''\tInstitute of Social Science, New Delhi \n* '''1996 - 1998'''\tThe Mahindra United World College of India, Mulshi, Maharashtra \n* '''1997 - 2002'''\tCorporate Headquarters, Kochi Refineries Limited, Kochi, Kerala \n* '''1998 - 2002'''\tYMCA International Campsite, Nilshi, Maharashtra \n* '''1998 - 1999'''\tQuest International School, Alibaug, Maharashtra\n* '''1998 - 2000'''\tTrailokya Bauddha Mahasangha Sahayaka Gana Girls' Hostel, Nagpur, Maharashtra\n* '''1999 - 2000'''\tStudent Village, Center for Development Studies and Activities, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''1999''' - \t        The Directorate of Town and Country Planning, Hyderabad, Telangana, (Competition Winner, Under Construction) \n* '''2001 - 2003'''\tBasant Bahar Housing, Ahmedabad, Gujarat\n* '''2001 - 2003'''\tCenturion hotel, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2001 - 2004'''\tCenter for Life Sciences Health and Medicine(previously CNDCM), Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2001 - 2002'''\tThimpu Structure Plan, Bhutan \n* '''2001 - 2004'''\tTAIN Square, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2003'''\t        Structure Plan for Gelephug, Damphu and Samtshi, Bhutan\n* '''2003'''\t        Urban design of the Dzong Precinct, Thimpu, Bhutan \n* '''2004 - 2007'''\tSamundra Institute of Maritime Studies, Lonavala, Maharashtra \n* '''2004 - 2005'''\tAshoka Primary School, Nasik, Maharashtra\n* '''2005 - 2009'''\tSuzlon One Earth Global Headquarters, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2005 - 2013'''\tRoyal Supreme Courts Complex, Thimphu, Bhutan\n* '''2005 - 2008'''\tNational Ceremonial Plaza, Thimphu, Bhutan\n* '''2006 - 2010'''\tBajaj IT Tower, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2006 - 2011'''\tIndian Institute of Management, Calcutta, West Bengal (Phase 1) \n* '''2006 - 2008'''\tAamby Valley International School, Lonavala, Maharashtra (Phase 1) \n* '''2006 - 2008'''\tIndia House, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2007 - 2009'''\tMirchandani Office Building, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2007 - 2013'''\tUN House, Thimphu, Bhutan\n* '''2007 - 2009'''\tSandhya Vakil House, Panvel\n* '''2007'''           \tCollege of Engineering Pune - Master Plan\n* '''2008 - 2010'''\tBajaj Science Educational Centre, Wardha, Maharashtra\n* '''2008 - 2013'''\tKirloskar Institute of Advanced Management Studies, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2008 -''' \t        Life Care Hospital and Research Centre, Udgir, Maharashtra\n* '''2009 -''' \t        Lodha Belmondo, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2009 - 2010'''\tStructure Plan for Denchi, Bhutan\n* '''2009 - 2012'''\tAcademic Building, College of Engineering, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2009 - 2012'''\tGirls' Hostel, College of Engineering, Pune, Maharashtra \n* '''2009''' - \t        Bajaj Institute of Technology, Wardha, Maharashtra\n* '''2010''' -           \tBajaj Management College, Nagpur, Maharashtra\n* '''2010''' -           \tAzim Premji University, Bengaluru, Karnataka\n* '''2011''' -      \tNew Era High School, Panchgani, Maharashtra \n* '''2011''' -      \t[[Indian Institute of Technology Hyderabad]], Telangana (Phase 1A)\n* '''2011 - 2013'''\tForbes Marshall Industrial Campus, Chakan, Pune (Phase 1)\n* '''2011'''-       \tIndian Institute of Management, Calcutta, West Bengal (Phase 2) \n* '''2013''' -      \t Indian Institute of Technology, Hyderabad, Telangana (Phase 1B)\n* '''2013''' -      \tNTTF, Katpadi, Tamil Nadu\n* '''2013''' -       \tEnvironmental Centre at Empress Garden, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2013''' -      \tKrohne Marshall Industrial Expansion, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2013''' -      \tKEM Hospital redevelopment, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2013''' -       \tBoys' Hostel, College of Engineering, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2014''' -      \tRedevelopment of Indrayani B, Pune, Maharashtra\n* '''2014''' -      \tForbes Marshall Industrial Campus, Chakan, Pune (Phase 2)\n\n==Awards and Recognition==\nIn April 2010 Professor Benninger was awarded the Architect for the Decade Award his contribution to the profession of architecture over that period. Over the past four years, on three occasions, the Indian Institute of Architects has honored him with the award of Best Public Building of the Year for his designs of the [[Centre for Life Sciences, Health and Medicine]], the [[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]] and for the [[Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies]].  The design for [[Suzlon One Earth]] has been honored by the Architects, Engineers, Surveyors Association of Pune as the Best Architectural Work in the City in 2009 and it was recently named the Most Sustainable Building in India, in a national competition. It is a [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum and Five Star [[Teri Griha]] building. Christopher Benninger is currently the sixth winner in India of the Golden Architect Award for Lifetime Achievement (2006) that was conferred in May 2007 by the A+D and Spectrum Foundation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://mobilepaper.timesofindia.com/mobile.aspx?article=yes&pageid=7&sectid=edid=&edlabel=PMIR&mydateHid=24-02-2010&pubname=Mirror+-+Pune&edname=&articleid=Ar00700&publabel=MM | title=AESA HONOUR FOR BENNINGER | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> Over the past seventeen years, six Indian architects have been honored with the Great Master's Award,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Master-of-concrete-dreams/258139/ |title=Expressindia.com |access-date=2010-06-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005150938/http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Master-of-concrete-dreams/258139/ |archive-date=2012-10-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and in 2007 Professor Benninger became the seventh awardee. Over several years he was recognised as one of the top ten architects in India by ''Construction World'' Magazine.<ref>[http://www.constructionupdate.com/asapp/events/CWABawards/archives_cw_2007.html Constructionupdate.com] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120722153643/http://www.constructionupdate.com/asapp/events/CWABawards/archives_cw_2007.html |date=2012-07-22 }}</ref>\nHis firm, Christopher Charles Benninger Architects, has a team of thirty-five professionals with studio in [[Pune]]. He has associated a group of technical consultants in New Delhi, Mumbai, Bangalore and Pune in the areas of structural services, landscape and interior design. CCBA offers comprehensive architectural services from design through supervision.  In recognition of his contributions to the architectural and planning professions in India, Christopher Charles Benninger has been honoured as the first recipient of the (RED) Recognition of Excellence in Design Award (2006). This was conferred by the [[Royal Society of Designers]] and\nArchitecture Plus Design journal in India on an Industrial Designer, on an Interior Designer and on an architect.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ekistics]]\n*[[Mahindra United World College of India]]\n*[[Principles of Intelligent Urbanism]]\n*[[Samundra Institute of Maritime Studies]]\n*[[Suzlon One Earth]]\n*[[YMCA International Camp, Nilshi, India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.ccba.in}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benninger, Christopher Charles}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American urban planners]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Design faculty]]\n[[Category:Architects from Ohio]]\n[[Category:American male artists of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American male artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American architects]]\n[[Category:People from Gainesville, Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Kalpaksolutions", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Charles_Benninger"}
